# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: operating-temperature
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The company was founded in 1983 by semiconductor veterans Robert Hartmann, Paul Newhagen, James Sansbury, and Michael Magranet with $1,300,000 in seed money.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The name of the company was a play on "alterable", the type of chips the company created.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The founders selected Rodney Smith to be the company's first CEO.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In 1988, Altera became a public company via an initial public offering (IPO).
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The main product lines from Altera are the Agilex FPGA product lines, and their predecessors: the high-end Stratix series, mid-range Arria series, and lower-cost Cyclone series; as well as the MAX series non-volatile FPGAs.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Altera and its partners offer an array of semiconductor intellectual property cores that serve as building blocks that design engineers can drop into their system designs to perform specific functions.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] IP cores eliminate some of the time-consuming tasks of creating every block in a design from scratch.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In 2000, Altera acquired Designpro and Northwest Logic, providers of IP cores, in order to expand its design capabilities and move towards delivery of complete system-on-chip solutions.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Beginning in December 2012, the company announced the shipment of its first system on a chip FPGA devices using a fully depleted silicon on insulator (FDSOI) 28 nm chip manufacturing process.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] These are the Cyclone V SoC devices, which have a dual-core ARM architecture Cortex-A9 processor system with FPGA logic on a single chip.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] These devices integrated FPGAs with full hard processor systems based around ARM architecture onto a single device.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] With these SoCs devices, users were able to create custom field-programmable SoC variants for power, board space, performance and cost optimization.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] As of 2025, the majority of Altera's FPGA devices are available as an SoC variant with an ARM hard processor system integrated with the FPGA as a single system on a chip.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Cyclone V SoC, Arria V SoC and Arria 10 SoC product families are system on a chip FPGAs based upon a hard ARM Cortex-A9 dual-core processor system.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Stratix 10 SoC and Agilex 7 SoC product families are system on a chip FPGAs based upon a hard ARM Cortex-A53 quad-core processor system.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The Agilex 5 SoC product family are system on a chip FPGAs based upon a hard ARM Cortex-A76/A55 quad-core processor system.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The Agilex 3 SoC product family are system on a chip FPGAs based upon a hard ARM Cortex-A55 dual-core processor system.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Altera offers the Nios V embedded soft processor cores based on the RISC-V instruction set architecture.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Previously Altera had offered their own proprietary Nios II embedded soft processor, the Freescale ColdFire v1 core, and the ARM Cortex-M1 processor.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] All of Altera's devices are supported by a common design environment, the Quartus Prime design software, which is a multi-platform development environment that includes various tools needed to design FPGAs, SoC FPGAs, and CPLDs.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In May 2013, Altera made available an SDK for OpenCL, enabling software programmers to access the high-performance capabilities of programmable logic devices.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Altera also supports high-level synthesis using SYCL extensions to ANSI C/C++.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In 1984, the company formed a partnership with Intel, licensing its programmable logic technology to Intel.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In 1994, Altera acquired the PLD business of Intel for $50 million.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In February 2013, Altera announced an agreement to use Intel's foundry services to produce its 14-nm node for the future manufacturing of its FPGAs, based on Intel's 14-nm tri-gate transistor technology, in place of Altera's ongoing agreement with TSMC.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The Stratix 10 product family was the first such product line.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In December 2015, Intel acquired Altera for $16.7 billion in cash.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Altera became Intel's newly formed business unit called the Programmable Solutions Group (PSG).
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In October 2023, Intel announced that at the start of 2024 it would begin a process of spinning off PSG into a separate company, while maintaining majority ownership and intending to seek an IPO within three years.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] In February 2024, Intel announced that the newly independent company would reestablish the Altera name and branding, and on January 1, 2025, Altera officially became an independent subsidiary of Intel.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] On April 14, 2025, Intel announced that they agreed to sell a 51% controlling stake to Silver Lake, a private equity firm.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] With this sale, Intel also cancelled their plan to conduct an IPO for the Altera business, since the majority stake is now owned by Silver Lake.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] It was announced that Raghib Hussain will replace Sandra Rivera as the chief executive officer of Altera, with an effective date of May 5, 2025.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] On September 15, 2025, Altera announced that Silver Lake completed the acquisition of a 51% stake in the company, while Intel holds the remaining 49%.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] On June 21, 2006, after an investigation by the U.S.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Securities and Exchange Commission, the company restated its financial results from 1996 to 2005 to correct accounting errors related to options backdating.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] The chief financial officer of the company resigned.
[src:operating-temperature/altera] Altera filed a petition to overturn related regulations but was, under Intel, denied in 2020.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] The company manufactures analog, mixed-signal and digital signal processing (DSP) integrated circuits (ICs) used in electronic equipment.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] These technologies are used to convert, condition and process real-world phenomena, such as light, sound, temperature, motion, and pressure into electrical signals.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices has approximately 100,000 customers in the following industries: communications, computer, instrumentation, military/aerospace, automotive, and consumer electronics applications.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices products include analog signal processing and digital signal processing technologies.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] These technologies include data converters, amplifiers, radio frequency (RF) technologies, embedded processors or digital signal processing (DSP) ICs, power management, and interface products.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] The company's data converter chips are used by National Instruments in high-precision measurement instrumentation systems.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Its data converters and amplifiers are also used by scientists and researchers in project "IceCube" – an underground neutrino telescope that uses digital optical modules (DOMS) to detect subatomic particles in the South Pole.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices had a line of micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) microphones until it sold that business to InvenSense in 2013.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices MEMS microphones were found in smart phones, tablet PCs, security systems, and medical applications.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] ADI's MEMS accelerometers were designed into game pad controllers by Microsoft, Logitech and Pellican.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] The company was founded by Ray Stata and Matthew Lorber, two MIT graduates, in 1965.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] The same year, the company released its first product, the Model 101 operational amplifier (op amp), which was a hockey-puck sized module used in test and measurement equipment.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 1967, the company published the first issue of its technical magazine, Analog Dialogue.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 1969, Analog Devices filed an initial public offering and became a publicly traded company.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Ten years later, the company was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 1973, the company was the first to launch laser trim wafers and the first CMOS digital-to-analog converter.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] By 1996, the company reported over $1 billion in company revenue.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] That same year, Jerald Fishman was named president and CEO, a position he held until his death in 2013 (see below).
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 2000, Analog Devices's sales grew by over 75% to $2.578 Billion and the company acquired five companies including BCO Technologies PLC, a manufacturer of thick film semiconductors, for $150 million.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] By 2004, Analog Devices had a customer base of 60,000 and its portfolio included over 10,000 products.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In January 2008, ON Semiconductor completed the acquisition of the CPU Voltage and PC Thermal Monitoring Business from Analog Devices., for $184 million.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 2012, the company led the worldwide data converter market with a 48.5% share, according to analyst firm Databeans.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Also, the company moved its listing from the NYSE to Nasdaq effective April 2, 2012.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In July 2016, Analog and Linear Technology agreed that Analog would acquire Linear in an approximately $14.8 billion cash and stock deal.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In July 2020, Analog agreed to acquire Maxim Integrated in an all stock deal that values the combined company at $68 billion.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices is headquartered in Wilmington, Massachusetts, with regional headquarters located in Shanghai, China; Munich, Germany; Limerick, Ireland; and Tokyo, Japan.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices has fabrication plants located in the United States and in Ireland.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] The company's testing facilities are located in General Trias, Philippines; Chonburi, Thailand; and Penang, Malaysia.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Design centers are located in Australia, Canada, China, Egypt, England, Germany, India, Italy, Japan, Scotland, Spain, Taiwan, Turkey and the United States.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Raymond Stata is a founder of Analog Devices and was responsible for the business strategy and product roadmap.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] After founding the company in 1965, Stata served as the company's chairman of the board of directors from 1973 to 2022, CEO from 1973 to 1996 and president from 1971 to 1991.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In addition, Stata is also a trustee of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, his alma mater and was awarded the IEEE Founders medal in 2003.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Stata received the EE Times "Lifetime Achievement" award in 2008.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Stata served as the chairman of the Semiconductor Industry Association for the year 2011.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Vincent Roche became president and CEO of Analog Devices in May 2013 and chairman of the board in June 2022.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] He first joined the company in 1988 as a marketing director in Limerick, Ireland.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Vincent Roche was ranked as part of The 25 Smartest CEOs in America (no.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Barrie Gilbert was named the first Technology Fellow of Analog Devices in 1979.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In addition, Gilbert was an IEEE Life Fellow and held over 65 patents.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Gilbert is best known for the "Gilbert cell" – an electronic multiplying mixer.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] At Analog Devices, Gilbert started the company's Northwest Labs design center in Oregon and continued to work on RF products crafted with high-speed nonlinear circuit techniques.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Paul Brokaw is an expert on integrated circuit design who has spent most of his career at Analog Devices, where he holds the position of Analog Fellow.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Brokaw is the inventor of many analog IC circuits, including the Brokaw bandgap reference and holds over 100 patents.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Robert Adams is Technical Fellow and manager of audio development at Analog Devices Inc.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Adams holds many patents related to the audio and electronic field.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] He is a member of the IEEE and a Fellow in the Audio Engineering Society.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Adams received a finalist ranking for the EDN Innovation and Innovator of the Year award in 1995.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Fishman was the CEO and president of Analog Devices from 1996 until his death on 28 March 2013.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 2004, Fishman was named CEO of the Year by Electronic Business.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] He was a 35-year veteran of Analog Devices and also served on the board of directors of Analog Devices, Cognex Corporation and Xilinx.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Mahdi Mohammad Sadeghi was fired after his arrest in 2024 on charges of providing material support to a terrorist organization.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Sadeghi was accused of evading U.S. sanctions by facilitating indirect sales of technology to the Iranian military, which was used by the Islamic Resistance in Iraq in the Tower 22 drone attack on a U.S. military outpost in 2024.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices sells linear, mixed-signal, MEMS and digital signal processing technologies for medical imaging, patient monitoring, medical instrumentation and home healthcare.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] The company's precision signal-processing components and Blackfin digital signal processors are included in Karmelsonix's Wholter, an overnight pulmonary monitor, and the Wheezometer, a personal asthmatic assessment device.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Accelerometers produced by Analog Devices are included in ZOLL Medical's PocketCPR, which measures the depth of chest compressions and provides audible and visual feedback to a rescuer to allow adjustment to proper depth and to the correct rate of compression.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In March 2024, the company announced that it had received U.S.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] FDA 510(k) clearance for Sensinel, a compact, wearable, non-invasive remote Cardiopulmonary Management (CPM) System that captures cardiopulmonary measurements for chronic disease management such as heart failure.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices develops components for safety systems, such as stability control systems and driver assistance systems, infotainment and interior applications.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Powertrain systems in hybrid and electric vehicles use high-precision data conversion products in battery monitoring and control systems.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In June 2025, ADI announced the formation of OpenGMSL Association to revolutionize the future on In-Vehicle Connectivity by creating a worldwide standard for transmission of video and high-speed data in the automotive ecosystem.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices industrial market includes process control systems that help drive productivity, energy efficiency and reliability.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 1967, Analog Devices first published *Analog Dialogue*.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Dan Sheingold took the position of editor two years later, which he held for over four decades.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] It is currently the longest-running in-house publication in the electronics industry.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In 2009, Analog Devices announced EngineerZone, an online technical support community.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] EngineerZone was launched so the design engineering community (customers, prospects, partners, employees and students) can ask questions, share knowledge and search for answers to their questions in an open forum.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] EngineerZone currently hosts over 100 English forums to discuss ADI products and share projects with other engineers.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Members are encouraged to self-serve by searching their rich knowledge base of FAQs and to respond to fellow member's threads.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] EZ China is also available for members seeking support in simplified Chinese.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Analog Devices offers reference circuits through its **Circuits from the Lab** program.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] These circuits are engineered and tested for quick system integration to help solve design challenges ranging from common to complex.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Reference circuits are smaller, modular designs that are more broadly applicable than application-specific reference designs.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] Each reference circuit is documented with test data, theory of operation, and component selection decision criteria.
[src:operating-temperature/analog-devices] In addition, reference circuits are tailored to meet real-world system integration needs and may also include board layout schematics, CAD tools models, device drivers, and evaluation hardware.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] In women, ovulation causes a sustained increase of at least 0.2 °C (0.4 °F) in BBT.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Monitoring BBTs is one way of estimating the day of ovulation.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] The tendency of a woman to have lower temperatures before ovulation, and higher temperatures afterwards, is known as a biphasic temperature pattern.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Charting this pattern may be used as a component of fertility awareness.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] The BBT of men is comparable to the BBT of women in their follicular phase.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] The higher levels of estrogen present during the pre-ovulatory (follicular) phase of the menstrual cycle lower BBTs.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] The higher levels of progesterone released by the corpus luteum after ovulation raise BBTs.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] After ovulation, the temperature will be raised by at least 0.2 °C (0.4 °F), for at least 72 hours, compared to the previous six days.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Charting of basal body temperatures is used in some methods of fertility awareness, such as the sympto-thermal method, and may be used to determine the onset of post-ovulatory infertility.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] When BBT alone is used to avoid a pregnancy, it is sometimes called the Temperature Rhythm method.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Basal body temperature alone is most effective at preventing pregnancy if the couple abstains from intercourse from the beginning of menstruation through the third day after the basal body temperature has risen.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] BBTs only show when ovulation has occurred; they do not predict ovulation.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Sperm typically lasts for at least three days and can survive as long as a week, making prediction of ovulation several days in advance necessary for avoiding pregnancy.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] There is limited evidence about the effectiveness of fertility awareness family planning methods, some of which use basal body temperature as one component.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] About 24% of women who use any type of fertility awareness program become pregnant during the first year, compared to about 85% of sexually active women who are not trying to prevent a pregnancy.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] The World Health Organization ranked fertility awareness methods, taken as a whole, as an "effective" method of preventing pregnancies.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] The WHO placed fertility awareness methods in the third tier of effectiveness, after "most effective" methods such as IUDs and "very effective" methods such as combined oral contraceptive pills.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Couples that are trying to conceive can use BBT to determine when the opportunity for a pregnancy during this cycle has passed.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Infertility due to lack of ovulation is common.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] BBT charts can be used to identify when and whether ovulation is taking place.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Regular menstrual cycles are often taken as evidence that a woman is ovulating normally, and irregular cycles is evidence she is not.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] However, many women with irregular cycles do ovulate normally, and some with regular cycles are actually anovulatory or have a luteal phase defect.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Records of basal body temperature can be used to accurately determine if a woman is ovulating.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-body-temperature] Calculating the expected due date for a pregnancy based upon the self-reported last menstrual period is less accurate than calculating it based upon either BBT or ultrasound.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Metabolism comprises the processes that the body needs to function.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Basal metabolic rate is the amount of energy per unit of time that a person needs to keep the body functioning at rest.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Some of those processes are breathing, blood circulation, controlling body temperature, cell growth, brain and nerve function, and contraction of muscles.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Basal metabolic rate affects the rate that a person burns calories and ultimately whether that individual maintains, gains, or loses weight.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The basal metabolic rate accounts for about 70% of the daily calorie expenditure by individuals.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In humans, BMR typically declines by 1–2% per decade after age 20, mostly due to loss of fat-free mass, although the variability between individuals is high.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The body's generation of heat is known as thermogenesis and it can be measured to determine the amount of energy expended.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR generally decreases with age, and with the decrease in lean body mass (as may happen with aging).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Increasing muscle mass has the effect of increasing BMR.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Aerobic (resistance) fitness level, a product of cardiovascular exercise, while previously thought to have effect on BMR, has been shown in the 1990s not to correlate with BMR when adjusted for fat-free body mass.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] But anaerobic exercise does increase resting energy consumption (see "aerobic vs. anaerobic exercise").
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Illness, previously consumed food and beverages, environmental temperature, and stress levels can affect one's overall energy expenditure as well as one's BMR.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR is measured under very restrictive circumstances when a person is awake.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] An accurate BMR measurement requires that the person's sympathetic nervous system not be stimulated, a condition which requires complete rest.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] A more common measurement, which uses less strict criteria, is resting metabolic rate (RMR).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR may be measured by gas analysis through either direct or indirect calorimetry, though a rough estimation can be acquired through an equation using age, sex, height, and weight.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] BMR is a flexible trait (it can be reversibly adjusted within individuals), with, for example, lower temperatures generally resulting in higher basal metabolic rates for both birds and rodents.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] There are two models to explain how BMR changes in response to temperature: the variable maximum model (VMM) and variable fraction model (VFM).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The VMM states that the summit metabolism (or the maximum metabolic rate in response to the cold) increases during the winter, and that the sustained metabolism (or the metabolic rate that can be indefinitely sustained) remains a constant fraction of the former.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The VFM says that the summit metabolism does not change, but that the sustained metabolism is a larger fraction of it.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The VMM is supported in mammals, and, when using whole-body rates, passerine birds.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The VFM is supported in studies of passerine birds using mass-specific metabolic rates (or metabolic rates per unit of mass).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This latter measurement has been criticized by Eric Liknes, Sarah Scott, and David Swanson, who say that mass-specific metabolic rates are inconsistent seasonally.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In addition to adjusting to temperature, BMR also may adjust before annual migration cycles.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] *islandica*) increases its BMR by about 40% before migrating northward.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This is because of the energetic demand of long-distance flights.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The increase is likely primarily due to increased mass in organs related to flight.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The end destination of migrants affects their BMR: yellow-rumped warblers migrating northward were found to have a 31% higher BMR than those migrating southward.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In humans, BMR is directly proportional to a person's lean body mass.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In other words, the more lean body mass a person has, the higher their BMR; but BMR is also affected by acute illnesses and increases with conditions like burns, fractures, infections, fevers, etc.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In menstruating females, BMR varies to some extent with the phases of their menstrual cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Due to the increase in progesterone, BMR rises at the start of the luteal phase and stays at its highest until this phase ends.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] There are different findings in research how much of an increase usually occurs.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Small sample, early studies, found various figures, such as; a 6% higher postovulatory sleep metabolism, a 7% to 15% higher 24 hour expenditure following ovulation, and an increase and a luteal phase BMR increase by up to 12%.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] A study by the American Society of Clinical Nutrition found that an experimental group of female volunteers had an 11.5% average increase in 24 hour energy expenditure in the two weeks following ovulation, with a range of 8% to 16%.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This group was measured via simultaneously direct and indirect calorimetry and had standardized daily meals and sedentary schedule in order to prevent the increase from being manipulated by change in food intake or activity level.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] A 2011 study conducted by the Mandya Institute of Medical Sciences found that during a woman's follicular phase and menstrual cycle is no significant difference in BMR, however the calories burned per hour is significantly higher, up to 18%, during the luteal phase.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Increased state anxiety (stress level) also temporarily increased BMR.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The primary organ responsible for regulating metabolism is the hypothalamus.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The hypothalamus is located on the diencephalon and forms the floor and part of the lateral walls of the third ventricle of the cerebrum.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] All of these functions taken together form a survival mechanism that causes us to sustain the body processes that BMR measures.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The basic metabolic rate varies between individuals.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] One 2005 study of 150 adults representative of the population in Scotland reported basal metabolic rates from as low as 1,027 kilocalories (4,300 kJ) per day to as high as 2,499 kilocalories (10,460 kJ), with a mean BMR of 1,500 kilocalories (6,300 kJ) per day.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Benedict showed that approximate values for BMR could be derived using body surface area (computed from height and weight), age, and sex, along with the oxygen and carbon dioxide measures taken from calorimetry.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Studies also showed that by eliminating the sex differences that occur with the accumulation of adipose tissue by expressing metabolic rate per unit of "fat-free" or lean body mass, the values between sexes for basal metabolism are essentially the same.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The aforementioned 2005 study in particular found that 62% of the variation in BMR among participants was explained by differences in fat free mass (FFM).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Other factors explaining the variation included fat mass (7%), age (2%), and experimental error including within-subject difference (2%).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The rest of the variation (27%) was unexplained.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This remaining difference was not explained by sex, leptin levels, triiodothyronine levels, or by differing tissue size of highly energetic organs such as the brain.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In a 2012 study of 8780 white obese subjects, it was found that body weight and fat-free mass had similar predictive power when used to estimate BMR, their respective combination with gender and age being able to explain 59% or 60% of the variation.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Gender plays a role in determining BMR in children and adolescents, but not in adults.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In addition, the age-related reduction in BMR is mostly explained by the decrease in FFM.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The BMR of the average person has also changed over time.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] A cross-sectional study of more than 1400 subjects in Europe and the US showed that once adjusted for differences in body composition (lean and fat mass) and age, BMR has fallen over the past 35 years.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The decline was also observed in a meta-analysis of more than 150 studies dating back to the early 1920s, translating into a decline in total energy expenditure of about 6%.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Several equations to predict the number of calories required by humans have been published from the early 20th–21st centuries.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Historically, accurate measurements of body composition were difficult to obtain.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] As technologies to measure lean body mass directly (e.g.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry) did not exist when early researchers developed these equations, they relied on total body weight, height, age, and sex as proxies for metabolic activity.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The difference in BMR for men and women is mainly due to differences in body mass.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] For example, a 55-year-old woman weighing 130 pounds (59 kg) and 66 inches (168 cm) tall would have a BMR of 1,272 kilocalories (5,320 kJ) per day.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In 1984, the original Harris–Benedict equations were revised using new data.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] where *s* is +5 for males and −161 for females.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] According to this formula, the woman in the example above has a BMR of 1,204 kilocalories (5,040 kJ) per day.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] During the last 100 years, lifestyles have changed, and Frankenfield *et al.* showed it to be about 5% more accurate.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The following formulas are based on a population of obese white people participating an Italian study.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] where *s* is 0 for females and 1 for males.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] These formulas take into account lean body mass, which makes them potentially more accurate for individuals with body compositions that differ significantly from the average (such as athletes and obese people).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The Katch–McArdle formula is used to predict resting daily energy expenditure (RDEE).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The Cunningham formula is commonly cited to predict RMR instead of BMR; however, the formulas provided by Katch–McArdle and Cunningham are the same.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] According to this formula, if the woman in the example has a body fat percentage of 30%, her resting daily energy expenditure (the authors use the term of basal and resting metabolism interchangeably) would be 1262 kcal per day.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Comparing the adult lean-mass formula to the adult body-mass formula, one finds that the weight of gender is markedly reduced.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] (In fact, the confidence interval of the slope includes 0, showing that gender has no statistically significant effect.) The slope for age is also markedly smaller, supporting the idea that age-related decline in BMR is mostly explained by loss of lean mass.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] About 70% of a human's total energy expenditure is due to the basal life processes taking place in the organs of the body (see table).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] About 20% of one's energy expenditure comes from physical activity and another 10% from thermogenesis, or digestion of food (*postprandial thermogenesis*).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] All of these processes require an intake of oxygen along with coenzymes to provide energy for survival (usually from macronutrients like carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) and expel carbon dioxide, due to processing by the Krebs cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] For the BMR, most of the energy is consumed in maintaining fluid levels in tissues through osmoregulation, and only about one-tenth is consumed for mechanical work, such as digestion, heartbeat, and breathing.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Exergonic reactions are energy-releasing reactions and are generally catabolic.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Endergonic reactions require energy and include anabolic reactions and the contraction of muscle.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Metabolism is the total of all catabolic, exergonic, anabolic, and endergonic reactions.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Adenosine triphosphate (ATP) is the intermediate molecule that drives the exergonic transfer of energy to switch to endergonic anabolic reactions used in muscle contraction.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This is what causes muscles to work which can require a breakdown, and also to build in the rest period, which occurs during the strengthening phase associated with muscular contraction.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] ATP is composed of adenine, a nitrogen containing base, ribose, a five carbon sugar (collectively called adenosine), and three phosphate groups.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] ATP is a high energy molecule because it stores large amounts of energy in the chemical bonds of the two terminal phosphate groups.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The breaking of these chemical bonds in the Krebs Cycle provides the energy needed for muscular contraction.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Because the ratio of hydrogen to oxygen atoms in all carbohydrates is always the same as that in water—that is, 2 to 1—all of the oxygen consumed by the cells is used to oxidize the carbon in the carbohydrate molecule to form carbon dioxide.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Consequently, during the complete oxidation of a glucose molecule, six molecules of carbon dioxide and six molecules of water are produced and six molecules of oxygen are consumed.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The chemical composition for fats differs from that of carbohydrates in that fats contain considerably fewer oxygen atoms in proportion to atoms of carbon and hydrogen.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] When listed on nutritional information tables, fats are generally divided into six categories: total fats, saturated fatty acid, polyunsaturated fatty acid, monounsaturated fatty acid, dietary cholesterol, and trans fatty acid.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] From a basal metabolic or resting metabolic perspective, more energy is needed to burn a saturated fatty acid than an unsaturated fatty acid.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The fatty acid molecule is broken down and categorized based on the number of carbon atoms in its molecular structure.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The chemical equation for metabolism of the twelve to sixteen carbon atoms in a saturated fatty acid molecule shows the difference between metabolism of carbohydrates and fatty acids.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Palmitic acid is a commonly studied example of the saturated fatty acid molecule.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Proteins are composed of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen arranged in a variety of ways to form a large combination of amino acids.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Unlike fat the body has no storage deposits of protein.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] All of it is contained in the body as important parts of tissues, blood hormones, and enzymes.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The structural components of the body that contain these amino acids are continually undergoing a process of breakdown and replacement.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Protein catabolism (breakdown) has been estimated to supply 10% to 15% of the total energy requirement during a two-hour aerobic training session.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This process could severely degrade the protein structures needed to maintain survival such as contractile properties of proteins in the heart, cellular mitochondria, myoglobin storage, and metabolic enzymes within muscles.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The oxidative system (aerobic) is the primary source of ATP supplied to the body at rest and during low intensity activities and uses primarily carbohydrates and fats as substrates.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Protein is not normally metabolized significantly, except during long term starvation and long bouts of exercise (greater than 90 minutes.) At rest approximately 70% of the ATP produced is derived from fats and 30% from carbohydrates.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Following the onset of activity, as the intensity of the exercise increases, there is a shift in substrate preference from fats to carbohydrates.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] During high intensity aerobic exercise, almost 100% of the energy is derived from carbohydrates, if an adequate supply is available.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Studies published in 1992 and 1997 indicate that the level of aerobic fitness of an individual does not have any correlation with the level of resting metabolism.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Both studies find that aerobic fitness levels do not improve the predictive power of fat free mass for resting metabolic rate.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] However, recent research from the Journal of Applied Physiology, published in 2012, compared resistance training and aerobic training on body mass and fat mass in overweight adults (STRRIDE AT/RT).
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] When time commitment is evaluated against health benefit, aerobic training is the optimal mode of exercise for reducing fat mass and body mass as a primary consideration, and resistance training is good as a secondary factor when aging and lean mass are a concern.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Resistance training causes injuries at a much higher rate than aerobic training.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Compared to resistance training, it was found that aerobic training resulted in a significantly more pronounced reduction of body weight by enhancing the cardiovascular system which is what is the principal factor in metabolic utilization of fat substrates.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Resistance training if time is available is also helpful in post-exercise metabolism, but it is an adjunctive factor because the body needs to heal sufficiently between resistance training episodes, whereas the body can accept aerobic training every day.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] RMR and BMR are measurements of daily consumption of calories.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The majority of studies that are published on this topic look at aerobic exercise because of its efficacy for health and weight management.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Anaerobic exercise, such as weight lifting, builds additional muscle mass.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Muscle contributes to the fat-free mass of an individual and therefore effective results from anaerobic exercise will increase BMR.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] However, the actual effect on BMR is controversial and difficult to enumerate.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Various studies suggest that the resting metabolic rate of trained muscle is around 55 kJ/kg per day; it then follows that even a substantial increase in muscle mass — say 5 kg — would make only a minor impact on BMR.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] In 1926, Raymond Pearl proposed that longevity varies inversely with basal metabolic rate (the "rate of living hypothesis").
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Additionally, the life span of houseflies can be extended by preventing physical activity.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] This theory has been bolstered by several new studies linking lower basal metabolic rate to increased life expectancy, across the animal kingdom—including humans.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Calorie restriction and reduced thyroid hormone levels, both of which decrease the metabolic rate, have been associated with higher longevity in animals.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] However, the ratio of total daily energy expenditure to resting metabolic rate can vary between 1.6 and 8.0 between species of mammals.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Animals also vary in the degree of coupling between oxidative phosphorylation and ATP production, the amount of saturated fat in mitochondrial membranes, the amount of DNA repair, and many other factors that affect maximum life span.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] One problem with understanding the associations of lifespan and metabolism is that changes in metabolism are often confounded by other factors that may affect lifespan.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] For example, under calorie restriction whole body metabolic rate goes down with increasing levels of restriction, but body temperature also follows the same pattern.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] By manipulating the ambient temperature and exposure to wind it was shown in mice and hamsters that body temperature is a more important modulator of lifespan than metabolic rate.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] A person's metabolism varies with their physical condition and activity.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Weight training can have a longer impact on metabolism than aerobic training, but there are no known mathematical formulas that can exactly predict the length and duration of a raised metabolism from trophic changes with anabolic neuromuscular training.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] A decrease in food intake will typically lower the metabolic rate as the body tries to conserve energy.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Researcher Gary Foster estimates that a very low calorie diet of fewer than 800 calories a day would reduce the metabolic rate by more than 10 percent.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The metabolic rate can be affected by some drugs: antithyroid agents (drugs used to treat hyper­thyroid­ism) such as propylthiouracil and methimazole bring the metabolic rate down to normal, restoring euthyroidism.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] Some research has focused on developing antiobesity drugs to raise the metabolic rate, such as drugs to stimulate thermogenesis in skeletal muscle.
[src:operating-temperature/basal-metabolic-rate] The metabolic rate may be elevated in stress, illness, and diabetes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A **circadian rhythm** (/sərˈkeɪdiən/), or **circadian cycle**, is a natural oscillation that repeats roughly every 24 hours.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms can refer to any process that originates within an organism (i.e., endogenous) and responds to the environment (is entrained by the environment).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms are regulated by a circadian clock whose primary function is to rhythmically co-ordinate biological processes so they occur at the correct time to maximize the fitness of an individual.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms have been widely observed in animals, plants, fungi and cyanobacteria and there is evidence that they evolved independently in each of these kingdoms of life.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The term *circadian* comes from the Latin **circa**, meaning "around", and **dies**, meaning "day".
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Processes with 24-hour cycles are more generally called **diurnal rhythms**; diurnal rhythms should not be called circadian rhythms unless they can be confirmed as endogenous, and not environmental.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Although circadian rhythms are endogenous, they are adjusted to the local environment by external cues called zeitgebers (from German **Zeitgeber** (German: [ˈtsaɪtˌɡeːbɐ]; lit.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] 'time giver')), which include light, temperature and redox cycles.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In clinical settings, an abnormal circadian rhythm in humans is known as a circadian rhythm sleep disorder.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The earliest recorded account of a circadian process is credited to Theophrastus, dating from the 4th century BC, probably provided to him by report of Androsthenes, a ship's captain serving under Alexander the Great.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Bretzl, in his book on the botanical findings of the Alexandrian campaigns.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In 1729, French scientist Jean-Jacques d'Ortous de Mairan conducted the first experiment designed to distinguish an endogenous clock from responses to daily stimuli.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] He noted that 24-hour patterns in the movement of the leaves of the plant *Mimosa pudica* persisted, even when the plants were kept in constant darkness.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In 1896, Patrick and Gilbert observed that during a prolonged period of sleep deprivation, sleepiness increases and decreases with a period of approximately 24 hours.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Szymanski showed that animals are capable of maintaining 24-hour activity patterns in the absence of external cues such as light and changes in temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In the early 20th century, circadian rhythms were noticed in the rhythmic feeding times of bees.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Auguste Forel, Ingeborg Beling, and Oskar Wahl conducted numerous experiments to determine whether this rhythm was attributable to an endogenous clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The existence of circadian rhythm was independently discovered in fruit flies in 1935 by two German zoologists, Hans Kalmus and Erwin Bünning.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In 1954, an important experiment reported by Colin Pittendrigh demonstrated that eclosion (the process of pupa turning into adult) in *Drosophila pseudoobscura* was a circadian behaviour.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] He demonstrated that while temperature played a vital role in eclosion rhythm, the period of eclosion was delayed but not stopped when temperature was decreased.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The term *circadian* was coined by Franz Halberg in 1959.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Ron Konopka and Seymour Benzer identified the first clock mutation in *Drosophila* in 1971, naming the gene "period" (*per*) gene, the first discovered genetic determinant of behavioral rhythmicity.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The *per* gene was isolated in 1984 by two teams of researchers.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Konopka, Jeffrey Hall, Michael Roshbash, and their team showed that the *per* locus is the centre of the circadian rhythm, and that loss of *per* stops circadian activity.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Young's team reported similar effects of *per*, and that the gene covers 7.1-kilobase (kb) interval on the X chromosome and encodes a 4.5-kb poly(A)+ RNA.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] They went on to discover the key genes and neurones in *Drosophila* circadian system, for which Hall, Rosbash, and Young received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 2017.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Joseph Takahashi discovered the first mammalian circadian clock mutation (*clockΔ19*) using mice in 1994.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, recent studies show that deletion of *clock* does not lead to a behavioral phenotype (the animals still have normal circadian rhythms), which questions its importance in rhythm generation.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The first human clock mutation was identified in an extended Utah family by Chris Jones, and genetically characterized by Ying-Hui Fu and Louis Ptacek.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Affected individuals are extreme 'morning larks' with 4-hour advanced sleep and other rhythms.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This form of familial advanced sleep phase syndrome is caused by a single amino acid change, S662➔G, in the human PER2 protein.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] **The rhythms are entrainable.** The rhythm can be reset by exposure to external stimuli (such as light and heat), a process called entrainment.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The external stimulus used to entrain a rhythm is called the zeitgeber, or "time giver".
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Travel across time zones illustrates the ability of the human biological clock to adjust to the local time; a person will usually experience jet lag before entrainment of their circadian clock has brought it into sync with local time.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] **The rhythms exhibit temperature compensation.** In other words, they maintain circadian periodicity over a range of physiological temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Many organisms live at a broad range of temperatures, and differences in thermal energy will affect the kinetics of all molecular processes in their cell(s).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In order to keep track of time, the organism's circadian clock must maintain roughly a 24-hour periodicity despite the changing kinetics, a property known as temperature compensation.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The Q10 temperature coefficient is a measure of this compensating effect.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] If the Q10 coefficient remains approximately 1 as temperature increases, the rhythm is considered to be temperature-compensated.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms allow organisms to anticipate and prepare for precise and regular environmental changes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] They thus enable organisms to make better use of environmental resources (e.g. light and food) compared to those that cannot predict such availability.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It has therefore been suggested that circadian rhythms put organisms at a selective advantage in evolutionary terms.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, rhythmicity appears to be as important in regulating and coordinating *internal* metabolic processes, as in coordinating with the *environment*.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] What drove circadian rhythms to evolve has been an enigmatic question.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Previous hypotheses emphasized that photosensitive proteins and circadian rhythms may have originated together in the earliest cells, with the purpose of protecting replicating DNA from high levels of damaging ultraviolet radiation during the daytime.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] As a result, replication was relegated to the dark.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, evidence for this is lacking: in fact the simplest organisms with a circadian rhythm, the cyanobacteria, do the opposite of this: they divide more in the daytime.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Recent studies instead highlight the importance of co-evolution of redox proteins with circadian oscillators in all three domains of life following the Great Oxidation Event approximately 2.3 billion years ago.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The current view is that circadian changes in environmental oxygen levels and the production of reactive oxygen species (ROS) in the presence of daylight are likely to have driven a need to evolve circadian rhythms to preempt, and therefore counteract, damaging redox reactions on a daily basis.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The simplest known circadian clocks are bacterial circadian rhythms, exemplified by the prokaryote cyanobacteria.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Recent research has demonstrated that the circadian clock of *Synechococcus elongatus* can be reconstituted *in vitro* with just the three proteins (KaiA, KaiB, and KaiC) of their central oscillator.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This clock has been shown to sustain a 22-hour rhythm over several days upon the addition of ATP.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Previous explanations of the prokaryotic circadian timekeeper were dependent upon a DNA transcription/translation feedback mechanism.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A defect in the human homologue of the *Drosophila* "period" gene was identified as a cause of the sleep disorder FASPS (Familial advanced sleep phase syndrome), underscoring the conserved nature of the molecular circadian clock through evolution.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Many more genetic components of the biological clock are now known.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Their interactions result in an interlocked feedback loop of gene products resulting in periodic fluctuations that the cells of the body interpret as a specific time of the day.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It is now known that the molecular circadian clock can function within a single cell.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This was shown by Gene Block in isolated mollusk basal retinal neurons (BRNs).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] At the same time, different cells may communicate with each other resulting in a synchronized output of electrical signaling.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] These may interface with endocrine glands of the brain to result in periodic release of hormones.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The receptors for these hormones may be located far across the body and synchronize the peripheral clocks of various organs.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Thus, the information of the time of the day as relayed by the eyes travels to the clock in the brain, and, through that, clocks in the rest of the body may be synchronized.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This is how the timing of, for example, sleep/wake, body temperature, thirst, and appetite are coordinately controlled by the biological clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythmicity is present in the sleeping and feeding patterns of animals, including human beings.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] There are also clear patterns of core body temperature, brain wave activity, hormone production, cell regeneration, and other biological activities.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In addition, photoperiodism, the physiological reaction of organisms to the length of day or night, is vital to both plants and animals, and the circadian system plays a role in the measurement and interpretation of day length.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Timely prediction of seasonal periods of weather conditions, food availability, or predator activity is crucial for survival of many species.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Although not the only parameter, the changing length of the photoperiod (day length) is the most predictive environmental cue for the seasonal timing of physiology and behavior, most notably for timing of migration, hibernation, and reproduction.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Mutations or deletions of clock genes in mice have demonstrated the importance of body clocks to ensure the proper timing of cellular/metabolic events; clock-mutant mice are hyperphagic and obese, and have altered glucose metabolism.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In mice, deletion of the Rev-ErbA alpha clock gene can result in diet-induced obesity and changes the balance between glucose and lipid utilization, predisposing to diabetes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, it is not clear whether there is a strong association between clock gene polymorphisms in humans and the susceptibility to develop the metabolic syndrome.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The rhythm is linked to the light–dark cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Animals, including humans, kept in total darkness for extended periods eventually function with a free-running rhythm.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Their sleep cycle is pushed back or forward each "day", depending on whether their "day", their endogenous period, is shorter or longer than 24 hours.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The environmental cues that reset the rhythms each day are called zeitgebers.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Totally blind subterranean mammals (e.g., blind mole rat *Spalax* sp.) are able to maintain their endogenous clocks in the apparent absence of external stimuli.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Although they lack image-forming eyes, their photoreceptors (which detect light) are still functional; they do surface periodically as well.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Free-running organisms that normally have one or two consolidated sleep episodes will still have them when in an environment shielded from external cues, but the rhythm is not entrained to the 24-hour light–dark cycle in nature.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The sleep–wake rhythm may, in these circumstances, become out of phase with other circadian or ultradian rhythms such as metabolic, hormonal, CNS electrical, or neurotransmitter rhythms.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Recent research has influenced the design of spacecraft environments, as systems that mimic the light–dark cycle have been found to be highly beneficial to astronauts.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Light therapy has been trialed as a treatment for sleep disorders.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Norwegian researchers at the University of Tromsø have shown that some Arctic animals (e.g., ptarmigan, reindeer) show circadian rhythms only in the parts of the year that have daily sunrises and sunsets.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In one study of reindeer, animals at 70 degrees North showed circadian rhythms in the autumn, winter and spring, but not in the summer.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Reindeer on Svalbard at 78 degrees North showed such rhythms only in autumn and spring.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The researchers suspect that other Arctic animals as well may not show circadian rhythms in the constant light of summer and the constant dark of winter.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A 2006 study in northern Alaska found that day-living ground squirrels and nocturnal porcupines strictly maintain their circadian rhythms through 82 days and nights of sunshine.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The researchers speculate that these two rodents notice that the apparent distance between the sun and the horizon is shortest once a day, and thus have a sufficient signal to entrain (adjust) by.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The navigation of the fall migration of the Eastern North American monarch butterfly (*Danaus plexippus*) to their overwintering grounds in central Mexico uses a time-compensated sun compass that depends upon a circadian clock in their antennae.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythm is also known to control mating behavioral in certain moth species such as *Spodoptera littoralis*, where females produce a specific pheromone that attracts and resets the male circadian rhythm to induce mating at night.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Although light is the primary synchronizer of the circadian rhythm through the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN), other environmental signals also influence the biological clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Feeding plays a key role in regulating peripheral clocks found in the liver, muscles, and adipose tissues.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Time-restricted feeding can adjust these clocks by modifying light signals.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Additionally, physical activity affects the circadian phase, notably by adjusting melatonin production and body temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Temperature itself is an important synchronizer, capable of modifying cellular circadian rhythms.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Finally, stress and the release of glucocorticoids influence the expression of clock genes, potentially disrupting biological cycles.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Integrating these factors is essential for understanding circadian rhythms beyond simple light regulation.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Plant circadian rhythms tell the plant what season it is and when to flower for the best chance of attracting pollinators.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Behaviors showing rhythms include leaf movement (nyctinasty), growth, germination, stomatal/gas exchange, enzyme activity, photosynthetic activity, and fragrance emission, among others.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms occur as a plant entrains to synchronize with the light cycle of its surrounding environment.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] These rhythms are endogenously generated, self-sustaining and are relatively constant over a range of ambient temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Important features include two interacting transcription-translation feedback loops: proteins containing PAS domains, which facilitate protein-protein interactions; and several photoreceptors that fine-tune the clock to different light conditions.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Anticipation of changes in the environment allows appropriate changes in a plant's physiological state, conferring an adaptive advantage.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A better understanding of plant circadian rhythms has applications in agriculture, such as helping farmers stagger crop harvests to extend crop availability and securing against massive losses due to weather.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Light is the signal by which plants synchronize their internal clocks to their environment and is sensed by a wide variety of photoreceptors.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Red and blue light are absorbed through several phytochromes and cryptochromes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Phytochrome A (phyA) is light labile and allows germination and de-etiolation when light is scarce.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Phytochromes B–E are more stable with phyB, the main phytochrome in seedlings grown in the light.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The cryptochrome (cry) gene is also a light-sensitive component of the circadian clock and is thought to be involved both as a photoreceptor and as part of the clock's endogenous pacemaker mechanism.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Cryptochromes 1–2 (involved in blue–UVA) help to maintain the period length in the clock through a whole range of light conditions.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The central oscillator generates a self-sustaining rhythm and is driven by two interacting feedback loops that are active at different times of day.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The morning loop consists of circadian and clock-associated 1 (CCA1) and late elongated hypocotyl (LHY), which encode closely related MYB transcription factors that regulate circadian rhythms in *Arabidopsis*, as well as pseudo-response regulators PRR7 and PRR9.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The evening loop consists of GI (Gigantea) and ELF4, both involved in regulation of flowering time genes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] When CCA1 and LHY are overexpressed (under constant light or dark conditions), plants become arrhythmic, and mRNA signals reduce, contributing to a negative feedback loop.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Gene expression of CCA1 and LHY oscillates and peaks in the early morning, whereas TOC1 gene expression oscillates and peaks in the early evening.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This finding and further computational modeling of TOC1 gene functions and interactions suggest a reframing of the plant circadian clock as a triple negative-component repressilator model rather than the positive/negative-element feedback loop characterizing the clock in mammals.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In 2018, researchers found that the expression of PRR5 and TOC1 hnRNA nascent transcripts follows the same oscillatory pattern as processed mRNA transcripts rhythmically in *A. thaliana*.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] LNKs binds to the 5'region of PRR5 and TOC1 and interacts with RNAP II and other transcription factors.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Moreover, RVE8-LNKs interaction enables a permissive histone-methylation pattern (H3K4me3) to be modified and the histone-modification itself parallels the oscillation of clock gene expression.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It has previously been found that matching a plant's circadian rhythm to its external environment's light and dark cycles has the potential to positively affect the plant.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Researchers came to this conclusion by performing experiments on three different varieties of *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] One of these varieties had a normal 24-hour circadian cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The other two varieties were mutated, one to have a circadian cycle of more than 27 hours, and one to have a shorter than normal circadian cycle of 20 hours.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The *Arabidopsis* with the 24-hour circadian cycle was grown in three different environments.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] One of these environments had a 20-hour light and dark cycle (10 hours of light and 10 hours of dark), the other had a 24-hour light and dark cycle (12 hours of light and 12 hours of dark), and the final environment had a 28-hour light and dark cycle (14 hours of light and 14 hours of dark).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The two mutated plants were grown in both an environment that had a 20-hour light and dark cycle and in an environment that had a 28-hour light and dark cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It was found that the variety of *Arabidopsis* with a 24-hour circadian rhythm cycle grew best in an environment that also had a 24-hour light and dark cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Overall, it was found that all the varieties of *Arabidopsis thaliana* had greater levels of chlorophyll and increased growth in environments whose light and dark cycles matched their circadian rhythm.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Researchers suggested that a reason for this could be that matching an *Arabidopsis*'s circadian rhythm to its environment could allow the plant to be better prepared for dawn and dusk, and thus be able to better synchronize its processes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In this study, it was also found that the genes that help to control chlorophyll peaked a few hours after dawn.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This appears to be consistent with the proposed phenomenon known as metabolic dawn.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] According to the metabolic dawn hypothesis, sugars produced by photosynthesis have potential to help regulate the circadian rhythm and certain photosynthetic and metabolic pathways.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] As the sun rises, more light becomes available, which normally allows more photosynthesis to occur.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The sugars produced by photosynthesis repress PRR7.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This repression of PRR7 then leads to the increased expression of CCA1.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] On the other hand, decreased photosynthetic sugar levels increase PRR7 expression and decrease CCA1 expression.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This feedback loop between CCA1 and PRR7 is what is proposed to cause metabolic dawn.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The molecular mechanism of circadian rhythm and light perception are best understood in *Drosophila*.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Clock genes are discovered from *Drosophila*, and they act together with the clock neurones.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] There are two unique rhythms, one during the process of hatching (called eclosion) from the pupa, and the other during mating.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The clock neurones are located in distinct clusters in the central brain.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The best-understood clock neurones are the large and small lateral ventral neurons (l-LNvs and s-LNvs) of the optic lobe.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] These neurones produce pigment dispersing factor (PDF), a neuropeptide that acts as a circadian neuromodulator between different clock neurones.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In the early morning, light activates the *cry* gene and its protein CRY causes the breakdown of TIM.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Thus PER/TIM dimer dissociates, and the unbound PER becomes unstable.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] PER undergoes progressive phosphorylation and ultimately degradation.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Absence of PER and TIM allows activation of *clk* and *cyc* genes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Thus, the clock is reset to start the next circadian cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This protein model was developed based on the oscillations of the PER and TIM proteins in the *Drosophila*.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It is based on its predecessor, the PER model where it was explained how the PER gene and its protein influence the biological clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The model includes the formation of a nuclear PER-TIM complex which influences the transcription of the PER and the TIM genes (by providing negative feedback) and the multiple phosphorylation of these two proteins.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The circadian oscillations of these two proteins seem to synchronise with the light-dark cycle even if they are not necessarily dependent on it.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Both PER and TIM proteins are phosphorylated and after they form the PER-TIM nuclear complex they return inside the nucleus to stop the expression of the PER and TIM mRNA.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This inhibition lasts as long as the protein, or the mRNA is not degraded.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] When this happens, the complex releases the inhibition.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Here can also be mentioned that the degradation of the TIM protein is sped up by light.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The primary circadian clock in mammals is located in the suprachiasmatic nucleus (or nuclei) (SCN), a pair of distinct groups of cells located in the hypothalamus.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Destruction of the SCN results in the complete absence of a regular sleep–wake rhythm.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The SCN receives information about illumination through the eyes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The retina of the eye contains "classical" photoreceptors ("rods" and "cones"), which are used for conventional vision.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] But the retina also contains specialized ganglion cells that are directly photosensitive, and project directly to the SCN, where they help in the entrainment (synchronization) of this master circadian clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The proteins involved in the SCN clock are homologous to those found in the fruit fly.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] These cells contain the photopigment melanopsin and their signals follow a pathway called the retinohypothalamic tract, leading to the SCN.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] If cells from the SCN are removed and cultured, they maintain their own rhythm in the absence of external cues.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The SCN takes the information on the lengths of the day and night from the retina, interprets it, and passes it on to the pineal gland, a tiny structure shaped like a pine cone and located on the epithalamus.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In response, the pineal secretes the hormone melatonin.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Secretion of melatonin peaks at night and ebbs during the day and its presence provides information about night-length.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Several studies have indicated that pineal melatonin feeds back on SCN rhythmicity to modulate circadian patterns of activity and other processes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, the nature and system-level significance of this feedback are unknown.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The circadian rhythms of humans can be entrained to slightly shorter and longer periods than the Earth's 24 hours.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Researchers at Harvard have shown that human subjects can at least be entrained to a 23.5-hour cycle and a 24.65-hour cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Early research into circadian rhythms suggested that most people preferred a day closer to 25 hours when isolated from external stimuli like daylight and timekeeping.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, this research was faulty because it failed to shield the participants from artificial light.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Although subjects were shielded from time cues (like clocks) and daylight, the researchers were not aware of the phase-delaying effects of indoor electric lights.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The subjects were allowed to turn on light when they were awake and to turn it off when they wanted to sleep.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Electric light in the evening delayed their circadian phase.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A more stringent study conducted in 1999 by Harvard University estimated the natural human rhythm to be closer to 24 hours and 11 minutes: much closer to the solar day.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Consistent with this research was a more recent study from 2010, which also identified sex differences, with the circadian period for women being slightly shorter (24.09 hours) than for men (24.19 hours).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In this study, women tended to wake up earlier than men and exhibit a greater preference for morning activities than men, although the underlying biological mechanisms for these differences are unknown.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] For temperature studies, subjects must remain awake but calm and semi-reclined in near darkness while their rectal temperatures are taken continuously.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Though variation is great among normal chronotypes, the average human adult's temperature reaches its minimum at about 5:00 a.m., about two hours before habitual wake time.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Baehr et al. found that, in young adults, the daily body temperature minimum occurred at about 04:00 (4 a.m.) for morning types, but at about 06:00 (6 a.m.) for evening types.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This minimum occurred at approximately the middle of the eight-hour sleep period for morning types, but closer to waking in evening types.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Melatonin is absent from the system or undetectably low during daytime.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Its onset in dim light, *dim-light melatonin onset* (DLMO), at roughly 21:00 (9 p.m.) can be measured in the blood or the saliva.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Its major metabolite can also be measured in morning urine.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Both DLMO and the midpoint (in time) of the presence of the hormone in the blood or saliva have been used as circadian markers.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] However, newer research indicates that the melatonin *offset* may be the more reliable marker.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Benloucif et al. found that melatonin phase markers were more stable and more highly correlated with the timing of sleep than the core temperature minimum.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] They found that both sleep offset and melatonin offset are more strongly correlated with phase markers than the onset of sleep.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In addition, the declining phase of the melatonin levels is more reliable and stable than the termination of melatonin synthesis.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In contradiction to previous studies, it has been found that there is no effect of body temperature on performance on psychological tests.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This is likely due to evolutionary pressures for higher cognitive function compared to the other areas of function examined in previous studies.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] More-or-less independent circadian rhythms are found in many organs and cells in the body outside the suprachiasmatic nuclei (SCN), the "master clock".
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Indeed, neuroscientist Joseph Takahashi and colleagues stated in a 2013 article that "almost every cell in the body contains a circadian clock".
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] For example, these clocks, called peripheral oscillators, have been found in the adrenal gland, oesophagus, lungs, liver, pancreas, spleen, thymus, and skin.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] There is also some evidence that the olfactory bulb and prostate may experience oscillations, at least when cultured.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Though oscillators in the skin respond to light, a systemic influence has not been proven.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In addition, many oscillators, such as liver cells, for example, have been shown to respond to inputs other than light, such as feeding.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Light resets the biological clock in accordance with the phase response curve (PRC).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Depending on the timing, light can advance or delay the circadian rhythm.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Both the PRC and the required illuminance vary from species to species, and lower light levels are required to reset the clocks in nocturnal rodents than in humans.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Light systems designed to support circadian rhythms, such as the CircadianLux ceiling round, can dynamically adjust lighting levels based on metrics such as melanopic equivalent daylight illuminance (M-EDI), aiming to better support the biological clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Various studies on humans have made use of enforced sleep/wake cycles strongly different from 24 hours, such as those conducted by Nathaniel Kleitman in 1938 (28 hours) and Derk-Jan Dijk and Charles Czeisler in the 1990s (20 hours).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Because people with a normal (typical) circadian clock cannot entrain to such abnormal day/night rhythms, this is referred to as a forced desynchrony protocol.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Studies also show that *Cyclosa turbinata* is unique in that its locomotor and web-building activity cause it to have an exceptionally short-period circadian clock, about 19 hours.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] When *C. turbinata* spiders are placed into chambers with periods of 19, 24, or 29 hours of evenly split light and dark, none of the spiders exhibited decreased longevity in their own circadian clock.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] These findings suggest that *C. turbinata* do not have the same costs of extreme desynchronization as do other species of animals.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The leading edge of circadian biology research is translation of basic body clock mechanisms into clinical tools, and this is especially relevant to the treatment of cardiovascular disease.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Timing of medical treatment in coordination with the body clock, chronotherapeutics, may also benefit patients with hypertension (high blood pressure) by significantly increasing efficacy and reduce drug toxicity or adverse reactions.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Drugs targeting the circadian clock mechanism (circadian pharmacology) have been shown experimentally to significantly reduce the damage due to heart attacks and prevent heart failure in rodent models.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Importantly, for rational translation of the most promising Circadian Medicine therapies to clinical practice, it is imperative that we understand how it helps treat disease in both biological sexes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Lighting requirements for circadian regulation are not simply the same as those for vision; planning of indoor lighting in offices and institutions is beginning to take this into account.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Animal studies on the effects of light in laboratory conditions have until recently considered light intensity (irradiance) but not color, which can be shown to "act as an essential regulator of biological timing in more natural settings".
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Blue LED lighting suppresses melatonin production five times more than the orange-yellow high-pressure sodium (HPS) light; a metal halide lamp, which is white light, suppresses melatonin at a rate more than three times greater than HPS.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Depression symptoms from long term nighttime light exposure can be undone by returning to a normal cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The NTSB cites this as contributing to many accidents, and has conducted several research studies in order to find methods of combating fatigue in pilots.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Studies conducted on both animals and humans show major bidirectional relationships between the circadian system and abusive drugs.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It is indicated that these abusive drugs affect the central circadian pacemaker.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Individuals with substance use disorder display disrupted rhythms.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] These disrupted rhythms can increase the risk for substance abuse and relapse.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It is possible that genetic and/or environmental disturbances to the normal sleep and wake cycle can increase the susceptibility to addiction.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] It is difficult to determine if a disturbance in the circadian rhythm is at fault for an increase in prevalence for substance abuse—or if other environmental factors such as stress are to blame.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Changes to the circadian rhythm and sleep occur once an individual begins abusing drugs and alcohol.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Once an individual stops using drugs and alcohol, the circadian rhythm continues to be disrupted.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The stabilization of sleep and the circadian rhythm might possibly help to reduce the vulnerability to addiction and reduce the chances of relapse.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms and clock genes expressed in brain regions outside the suprachiasmatic nucleus may significantly influence the effects produced by drugs such as cocaine.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Moreover, genetic manipulations of clock genes profoundly affect cocaine's actions.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Disruption to rhythms usually has a negative effect.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Many travelers have experienced the condition known as jet lag, with a number of associated symptoms of fatigue, disorientation, insomnia, indigestion, inability to sleep, appetite loss, irritability, headache, and obesity.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Disruption to rhythms in the longer term is believed to have significant adverse health consequences for peripheral organs outside the brain, in particular in the development or exacerbation of cardiovascular disease.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Studies have shown that maintaining normal sleep and circadian rhythms is important for many aspects of brain and health.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A number of studies have also indicated that a power-nap, a short period of sleep during the day, can reduce stress and may improve productivity without any measurable effect on normal circadian rhythms.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms also play a part in the reticular activating system, which is crucial for maintaining a state of consciousness.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] A reversal in the sleep–wake cycle may be a sign or complication of uremia, azotemia or acute kidney injury.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Studies have also helped elucidate how light has a direct effect on human health through its influence on the circadian biology.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] One of the first studies to determine how disruption of circadian rhythms causes cardiovascular disease was performed in the Tau hamsters, which have a genetic defect in their circadian clock mechanism.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] When maintained in a 24-hour light-dark cycle that was "out of sync" with their normal 22 circadian mechanism they developed profound cardiovascular and renal disease; it impacts cardiovascular physiopathology and its function (e.g., heart rate, blood pressure).
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] This impact was studied within shift workers by comparing C-reactive protein and blood pressure levels in two experimental groups.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Results showed an increase of 11% in 24h hs-CRP, as well as in systolic and diastolic blood pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Disruption of circadian clocks can also be a critical risk factor for hypertension, ischemic stroke, coronary heart disease, or sudden cardiac death.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] The adverse effects of circadian misalignment on human physiology has been studied in the laboratory using a misalignment protocol, and by studying shift workers.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian misalignment is associated with many risk factors of cardiovascular disease.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] High levels of the atherosclerosis biomarker, resistin, have been reported in shift workers indicating the link between circadian misalignment and plaque build up in arteries.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Additionally, elevated triacylglyceride levels (molecules used to store excess fatty acids) were observed and contribute to the hardening of arteries, which is associated with cardiovascular diseases including heart attack, stroke and heart disease.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Shift work and the resulting circadian misalignment is also associated with hypertension.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Shift work or chronic jet lag have profound consequences for circadian and metabolic events in the body.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Animals that are forced to eat during their resting period show increased body mass and altered expression of clock and metabolic genes.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] In humans, shift work that favours irregular eating times is associated with altered insulin sensitivity, diabetes and higher body mass.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Reduced cognitive function (e.g., alertness, mood, social activities, physical performance) has been associated with circadian misalignment.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Chronic shift workers display increased rates of operational error, impaired visual-motor performance and processing efficacy which can lead to both a reduction in performance and potential safety issues.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Increased risk of dementia is associated with chronic night shift workers compared to day shift workers, particularly for individuals over 50 years old.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Sleep deprivation has been shown to decrease both cognitive and physical performance.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Studies on the differences in circadian rhythm between the sexes have indicated that women may have earlier circadian timing, with light conditions as a possible factor.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Disruptions in circadian rhythms in females may increase the odds of menstrual cycle disruption and infertility, while in males, the disruption in circadian rhythm may lead to decreased semen quality.
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Young, and Michael Rosbash were awarded Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine "for their discoveries of molecular mechanisms controlling the circadian rhythm".
[src:operating-temperature/circadian-rhythm] Circadian rhythms was taken as an example of scientific knowledge being transferred into the public sphere.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Components are often designed to generate as little heat as possible, and computers and operating systems may be designed to reduce power consumption and consequent heating according to workload, but more heat may still be produced than can be removed without attention to cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Use of heatsinks cooled by airflow reduces the temperature rise produced by a given amount of heat.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Attention to patterns of airflow can prevent the development of hotspots.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Computer fans are widely used along with heatsink fans to reduce temperature by actively exhausting hot air.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] There are also other cooling techniques, such as liquid cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] All modern day processors are designed to cut out or reduce their voltage or clock speed if the internal temperature of the processor exceeds a specified limit.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This is generally known as *thermal throttling* in the case of reduction of clock speeds, or *thermal shutdown* in the case of a complete shutdown of the device or system.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Cooling may be designed to reduce the ambient temperature within the case of a computer, such as by exhausting hot air, or to cool a single component or small area (spot cooling).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Components commonly individually cooled include the CPU, graphics processing unit (GPU) and the northbridge.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] CPU and GPU) are the main generators of heat in modern computers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat generation can be reduced by efficient design and selection of operating parameters such as voltage and frequency, but ultimately, acceptable performance can often only be achieved by managing significant heat generation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In operation, the temperature of a computer's components will rise until the heat transferred to the surroundings is equal to the heat produced by the component, that is, when thermal equilibrium is reached.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] For reliable operation, the temperature must never exceed a specified maximum permissible value unique to each component.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] For semiconductors, instantaneous junction temperature, rather than component case, heatsink, or ambient temperature is critical.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Because high temperatures can significantly reduce life span or cause permanent damage to components, and the heat output of components can sometimes exceed the computer's cooling capacity, manufacturers often take additional precautions to ensure that temperatures remain within safe limits.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A computer with thermal sensors integrated in the CPU, motherboard, chipset, or GPU can shut itself down when high temperatures are detected to prevent permanent damage, although this may not completely guarantee long-term safe operation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Before an overheating component reaches this point, it may be "throttled" until temperatures fall below a safe point using dynamic frequency scaling technology.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Throttling reduces the operating frequency and voltage of an integrated circuit or disables non-essential features of the chip to reduce heat output, often at the cost of slightly or significantly reduced performance.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] For desktop and notebook computers, throttling is often controlled at the BIOS level.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Throttling is also commonly used to manage temperatures in smartphones and tablets, where components are packed tightly together with little to no active cooling, and with additional heat transferred from the hand of the user.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The user can also perform several tasks in order to pre-emptively prevent damage from happening.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] They can perform a visual inspection of the cooler and case fans.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] If any of them are not spinning correctly, it is likely that they will need to be replaced.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The user should also clean the fans thoroughly, since dust and debris can increase the ambient case temperature and impact fan performance.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The best way to do so is with compressed air in an open space.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Another pre-emptive technique to prevent damage is to replace the thermal paste regularly.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] As electronic computers became larger and more complex, cooling of the active components became a critical factor for reliable operation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Early vacuum-tube computers, with relatively large cabinets, could rely on natural or forced air circulation for cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] However, solid-state devices were packed much more densely and had lower allowable operating temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Starting in 1965, IBM and other manufacturers of mainframe computers sponsored intensive research into the physics of cooling densely packed integrated circuits.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Many air and liquid cooling systems were devised and investigated, using methods such as natural and forced convection, direct air impingement, direct liquid immersion and forced convection, pool boiling, falling films, flow boiling, and liquid jet impingement.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Mathematical analysis was used to predict temperature rises of components for each possible cooling system geometry.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] IBM developed three generations of the Thermal Conduction Module (TCM) which used a water-cooled cold plate in direct thermal contact with integrated circuit packages.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Each package had a thermally conductive pin pressed onto it, and helium gas surrounded chips and heat-conducting pins.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The design could remove up to 27 watts from a chip and up to 2000 watts per module, while maintaining chip package temperatures of around 50 °C (122 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In the IBM 3081 processor, TCMs allowed up to 2700 watts on a single printed circuit board while maintaining chip temperature at 69 °C (156 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Thermal conduction modules using water cooling were also used in mainframe systems manufactured by other companies including Mitsubishi and Fujitsu.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The Cray-1 supercomputer designed in 1976 had a distinctive cooling system.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The machine was only 77 inches (2,000 mm) in height and 56+1⁄2 inches (1,440 mm) in diameter, and consumed up to 115 kilowatts; this is comparable to the average power consumption of a few dozen Western homes or a medium-sized car.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The integrated circuits used in the machine were the fastest available at the time, using emitter-coupled logic; however, the speed was accompanied by high power consumption compared to later CMOS devices.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Refrigerant was circulated through piping embedded in vertical cooling bars in twelve columnar sections of the machine.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Each of the 1662 printed circuit modules of the machine had a copper core and was clamped to the cooling bar.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The system was designed to maintain the cases of integrated circuits at no more than 54 °C (129 °F), with refrigerant circulating at 21 °C (70 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Final heat rejection was through a water-cooled condenser.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Piping, heat exchangers, and pumps for the cooling system were arranged in an upholstered bench seat around the outside of the base of the computer.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] About 20 percent of the machine's weight in operation was refrigerant.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In the later Cray-2, with its more densely packed modules, Seymour Cray had trouble effectively cooling the machine using the metal conduction technique with mechanical refrigeration, so he switched to 'liquid immersion' cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This method involved filling the chassis of the Cray-2 with a liquid called Fluorinert.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fluorinert, as its name implies, is an inert liquid that does not interfere with the operation of electronic components.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] As the components came to operating temperature, the heat would dissipate into the Fluorinert, which was pumped out of the machine to a chilled water heat exchanger.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Performance per watt of modern systems has greatly improved; many more computations can be carried out with a given power consumption than was possible with the integrated circuits of the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Recent supercomputer projects such as Blue Gene rely on air cooling, which reduces cost, complexity, and size of systems compared to liquid cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A component may be fitted in good thermal contact with a heatsink, a passive device with large thermal capacity and with a large surface area relative to its volume.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heatsinks are usually made of a metal with high thermal conductivity such as aluminium or copper, and incorporate fins to increase surface area.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat from a relatively small component is transferred to the larger heatsink; the equilibrium temperature of the component plus heatsink is much lower than the component's alone would be.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat is carried away from the heatsink by convective or fan-forced airflow.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fan cooling is often used to cool processors and graphics cards that consume significant amounts of electrical energy.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In a computer, a typical heat-generating component may be manufactured with a flat surface.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A block of metal with a corresponding flat surface and finned construction, sometimes with an attached fan, is clamped to the component.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] To fill poorly conducting air gaps due to imperfectly flat and smooth surfaces, a thin layer of thermal grease, a thermal pad, or thermal adhesive may be placed between the component and heatsink.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat is removed from the heatsink by convection, to some extent by radiation, and possibly by conduction if the heatsink is in thermal contact with, say, the metal case.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Inexpensive fan-cooled aluminium heatsinks are often used on standard desktop computers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heatsinks with copper base-plates, or made of copper, have better thermal characteristics than those made of aluminium.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A copper heatsink is more effective than an aluminium unit of the same size, which is relevant with regard to the high-power-consumption components used in high-performance computers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Passive heatsinks are commonly found on older CPUs, parts that do not dissipate much power (such as the chipset), computers with low-power processors, and equipment where silent operation is critical and fan noise unacceptable.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Usually a heatsink is clamped to the integrated heat spreader (IHS), a flat metal plate the size of the CPU package which is part of the CPU assembly and spreads the heat locally.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A thin layer of thermal compound is placed between them to compensate for surface imperfections.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The spreader's primary purpose is to redistribute heat.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The heatsink fins improve its efficiency.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Several brands of DDR2, DDR3, DDR4 and DDR5 DRAM memory modules are fitted with a finned heatsink clipped onto the top edge of the module.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The same technique is used for video cards that use a finned passive heatsink on the GPU.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Higher-end M.2 SSDs can be prone to significant heat generation, and as a result these may be sold with a heatsink included, or alternatively a third-party heatsink may be attached by the user during installation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fan-cooled aluminium heatsinks were originally the norm for desktop computers, but nowadays many heatsinks feature copper base plate, copper base circle, or are entirely made of copper.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Dust tends to build up in the crevices of finned heatsinks, particularly with the high airflow produced by fans.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This keeps the air away from the hot component, reducing cooling effectiveness; however, removing the dust restores effectiveness.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Passive heatsink cooling involves attaching a block of machined or extruded metal to the part that needs cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] More commonly for a personal computer CPU, a clamp holds the heatsink directly over the chip, with a thermal grease or thermal pad spread between.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This block has fins and ridges to increase its surface area.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The heat conductivity of metal is much better than that of air, and it radiates heat better than the component that it is protecting (usually an integrated circuit or CPU).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Dust build-up between the metal fins of a heatsink gradually reduces efficiency, but can be countered with a gas duster by blowing away the dust along with any other unwanted excess material.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Passive heatsinks are commonly found on older CPUs, parts that do not get very hot (such as the chipset), low-power computers, and embedded devices.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Many smartphones use only passive cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Usually a heatsink is attached to the integrated heat spreader (IHS), essentially a large, flat plate attached to the CPU, with conduction paste layered between.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This dissipates or spreads the heat locally.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Unlike a heatsink, a spreader is meant to redistribute heat, not to remove it.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In addition, the IHS protects the fragile CPU.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Passive cooling involves no fan noise, as convection moves air over the heatsink.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fans are used when natural convection is insufficient to remove heat.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fans may be fitted to the computer case or attached to CPUs, GPUs, chipsets, power supply units (PSUs), hard drives, or as cards plugged into an expansion slot.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] 200, 230, 250 and 300 mm fans are sometimes used in high-performance personal computers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A computer has a certain resistance to air flowing through the chassis and components.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This is the sum of all the smaller impediments to air flow, such as the inlet and outlet openings, air filters, internal chassis, and electronic components.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fans are simple air pumps that provide pressure to the air of the inlet side relative to the output side.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] That pressure difference moves air through the chassis, with air flowing to areas of lower pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fans generally have two published specifications: free air flow and maximum differential pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Free air flow is the amount of air a fan will move with zero back-pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Maximum differential pressure is the amount of pressure a fan can generate when completely blocked.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In between these two extremes are a series of corresponding measurements of flow versus pressure which is usually presented as a graph.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Each fan model will have a unique curve, like the dashed curves in the adjacent illustration.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Fans can be installed parallel to each other, in series, or a combination of both.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Parallel installation would be fans mounted side by side.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Series installation would be a second fan in line with another fan such as an inlet fan and an exhaust fan.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] To simplify the discussion, it is assumed the fans are the same model.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Parallel fans will provide double the free air flow but no additional driving pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Series installation, on the other hand, will double the available static pressure but not increase the free air flow rate.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The adjacent illustration shows a single fan versus two fans in parallel with a maximum pressure of 0.15 inches (3.8 mm) of water and a doubled flow rate of about 72 cubic feet per minute (2.0 m3/min).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Note that air flow changes as the square root of the pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Thus, doubling the pressure will only increase the flow 1.41 (√2) times, not twice as might be assumed.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Another way of looking at this is that the pressure must go up by a factor of four to double the flow rate.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] To determine flow rate through a chassis, the chassis impedance curve can be measured by imposing an arbitrary pressure at the inlet to the chassis and measuring the flow through the chassis.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This requires fairly sophisticated equipment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] With the chassis impedance curve (represented by the solid red and black lines on the adjacent curve) determined, the actual flow through the chassis as generated by a particular fan configuration is graphically shown where the chassis impedance curve crosses the fan curve.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The slope of the chassis impedance curve is a square root function, where doubling the flow rate required four times the differential pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In this particular example, adding a second fan provided marginal improvement with the flow for both configurations being approximately 27–28 cubic feet per minute (0.76–0.79 m3/min).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] While not shown on the plot, a second fan in series would provide slightly better performance than the parallel installation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This would be actual flow through the chassis and not the free air rating of the fan.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] It should also be noted that "Q", the heat transferred, is a function of the heat transfer efficiency of a CPU or GPU cooler to the airflow.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A "dual piezo cooling jet", patented by GE, uses vibrations to pump air through the device.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The initial device is three millimetres thick and consists of two nickel discs that are connected on either side to a sliver of piezoelectric ceramics.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] An alternating current passed through the ceramic component causes it to expand and contract at up to 150 times per second so that the nickel discs act like a bellows.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Contracted, the edges of the discs are pushed apart and suck in hot air.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Expanding brings the nickel discs together, expelling the air at high velocity.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The device has no bearings and does not require a motor.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] It is thinner and consumes less energy than typical fans.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The jet can move the same amount of air as a cooling fan twice its size while consuming half as much electricity and at lower cost.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The cooling technology under development by Kronos and Thorn Micro Technologies employs a device called an ionic wind pump (also known as an electrostatic fluid accelerator).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The basic operating principle of an ionic wind pump is corona discharge, an electrical discharge near a charged conductor caused by the ionization of the surrounding air.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The corona discharge cooler developed by Kronos works in the following manner: A high electric field is created at the tip of the cathode, which is placed on one side of the CPU.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The high energy potential causes the oxygen and nitrogen molecules in the air to become ionized (positively charged) and create a corona (a halo of charged particles).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Placing a grounded anode at the opposite end of the CPU causes the charged ions in the corona to accelerate towards the anode, colliding with neutral air molecules on the way.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] During these collisions, momentum is transferred from the ionized gas to the neutral air molecules, resulting in movement of gas towards the anode.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The advantages of the corona-based cooler are its lack of moving parts, thereby eliminating certain reliability issues and operating with a near-zero noise level and moderate energy consumption.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A heat pipe is a hollow tube containing a heat transfer liquid.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The liquid absorbs heat and evaporates at one end of the pipe.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The vapor travels to the other (cooler) end of the tube, where it condenses, giving up its latent heat.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The liquid returns to the hot end of the tube by gravity or capillary action and repeats the cycle.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat pipes have a much higher effective thermal conductivity than solid materials.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] For use in computers, the heatsink on the CPU is attached to a larger radiator heatsink.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Both heatsinks are hollow, as is the attachment between them, creating one large heat pipe that transfers heat from the CPU to the radiator, which is then cooled using some conventional method.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This method is usually used when space is tight, as in small form-factor PCs and laptops, or where no fan noise can be tolerated, as in audio production.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Because of the efficiency of this method of cooling, many desktop CPUs and GPUs, as well as high end chipsets, use heat pipes or vapor chambers in addition to active fan-based cooling and passive heatsinks to remain within safe operating temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A vapor chamber operates on the same principles as a heat pipe but takes on the form of a slab or sheet instead of a pipe.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat pipes may be placed vertically on top and form part of vapor chambers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Vapor chambers may also be used on high-end smartphones.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquid cooling is a highly effective method of removing excess heat, with the most common heat transfer fluid in desktop PCs being distilled water with additives.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The advantages of water cooling over air cooling include water's higher specific heat capacity and thermal conductivity.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquid cooling is typically combined with air cooling, using liquid cooling for the hottest components while retaining simpler and cheaper air cooling for less demanding components.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The radiator is itself usually cooled additionally by means of a fan.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Besides a fan, it could possibly also be cooled by other means, such as a Peltier cooler (although Peltier elements are most commonly placed directly on top of the hardware to be cooled, and the coolant is used to conduct the heat away from the hot side of the Peltier element).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A coolant reservoir is often also connected to the system.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Besides active liquid cooling systems, passive liquid cooling systems are also sometimes used.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] These systems often leave out a fan or a water pump, theoretically increasing their reliability and making them quieter than active systems.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The downsides of these systems are that they are much less efficient in discarding the heat and thus need much more coolant—and a commensurately larger reservoir— to give it time to cool down.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquids allow the transfer of more heat from the parts being cooled than air, making liquid cooling suitable for high-performance computer applications.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Compared to air cooling, liquid cooling is also influenced less by the ambient temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquid cooling allows more flexibility in the placement of the radiator, making it easier to optimize cooling inside a case and expel hot air out, compared to air coolers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] While liquid cooling reduces noise levels from better cooling performance and thus slower fan speeds, the pumps used to circulate the liquid often run at high RPMs and can be noisy.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Disadvantages of liquid cooling include complexity and the potential for a coolant leak.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Leaking water (and any additives in the water) can damage electronic components with which it comes into contact, and the need to test for and repair leaks makes for more complex and less reliable installations.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] While originally limited to mainframe computers, liquid cooling has become a practice largely associated with overclocking in the form of either manufactured all-in-one (AIO) kits or do-it-yourself setups assembled from individually gathered parts.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Following the invention of the closed-loop liquid cooler (AIO) by Asetek, the 2010s have seen an increase in the popularity of liquid cooling in pre-assembled, moderate to high performance, desktop computers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Sealed closed-loop systems incorporating a pre-filled radiator, fan or fans, and waterblock incorporating a pump simplify the installation and maintenance of water cooling at a slight cost in cooling effectiveness relative to larger and more complex setups.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Additional uses of the heat carried by liquid cooling have been demonstrated.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The IBM Aquasar system uses *hot water cooling* to achieve energy efficiency and the water being used to heat buildings as well.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Alternately, a new breed of the cooling system is being developed, inserting a pump into the thermosiphon loop.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This adds another degree of flexibility for the design engineer, as the heat can now be effectively transported away from the heat source and either reclaimed or dissipated to ambient.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Junction temperature can be tuned by adjusting the system pressure; higher pressure equals higher fluid saturation temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This allows for smaller condensers, smaller fans, and/or the effective dissipation of heat in a high ambient temperature environment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] These systems are, in essence, the next-generation fluid cooling paradigm, as they are approximately 10 times more efficient than single-phase water.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Since the system uses a dielectric as the heat transport medium, leaks do not cause a catastrophic failure of the electric system.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A "thermosiphon" traditionally refers to a closed system consisting of several pipes and/or chambers, with a larger chamber containing a small reservoir of liquid (often having a boiling point just above ambient temperature, but not necessarily).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The larger chamber is as close to the heat source and designed to conduct as much heat from it into the liquid as possible, for example, a CPU cold plate with the chamber inside it filled with the liquid.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Conventional cooling techniques all attach their "cooling" component to the outside of the computer chip package.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This "attaching" technique will always exhibit some thermal resistance, reducing its effectiveness.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The heat can be more efficiently and quickly removed by directly cooling the local hot spots of the chip, within the package.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] At these locations, power dissipation of over 300 W/cm2 (typical CPU is less than 100 W/cm2) can occur, although future systems are expected to exceed 1000 W/cm2.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This form of local cooling is essential to developing high power density chips.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This ideology has led to the investigation of integrating cooling elements into the computer chip.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Currently there are two techniques: micro-channel heatsinks, and jet impingement cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In micro-channel heatsinks, channels are fabricated into the silicon chip (CPU), and coolant is pumped through them.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The channels are designed with very large surface area which results in large heat transfers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat dissipation of 3000 W/cm2 has been reported with this technique.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The heat dissipation can be further increased if two-phase flow cooling is applied.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Unfortunately, the system requires large pressure drops, due to the small channels, and the heat flux is lower with dielectric coolants used in electronic cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Another local chip cooling technique is jet impingement cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In this technique, a coolant is flowed through a small orifice to form a jet.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The jet is directed toward the surface of the CPU chip, and can effectively remove large heat fluxes.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Heat dissipation of over 1000 W/cm2 has been reported.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The system can be operated at lower pressure in comparison to the micro-channel method.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The heat transfer can be further increased using two-phase flow cooling and by integrating return flow channels (hybrid between micro-channel heatsinks and jet impingement cooling).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] As liquid nitrogen boils at −196 °C (−320.8 °F), far below the freezing point of water, it is valuable as an extreme coolant for short overclocking sessions.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In a typical installation of liquid nitrogen cooling, a copper or aluminium pipe is mounted on top of the processor or graphics card.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] After the system has been heavily insulated against condensation, the liquid nitrogen is poured into the pipe, resulting in temperatures well below −100 °C (−148 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Evaporation devices ranging from cut out heatsinks with pipes attached to custom-milled copper containers are used to hold the nitrogen as well as to prevent large temperature changes.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] However, after the nitrogen evaporates, it has to be refilled.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] In the realm of personal computers, this method of cooling is seldom used in contexts other than overclocking trial runs and record-setting attempts, as the CPU will usually expire within a relatively short period of time due to temperature stress caused by changes in internal temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Although liquid nitrogen is non-flammable, it can condense oxygen directly from air.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Mixtures of liquid oxygen and flammable materials can be dangerously explosive.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquid nitrogen cooling is, generally, only used for processor benchmarking, due to the fact that continuous usage may cause permanent damage to one or more parts of the computer and, if handled in a careless way, can even harm the user, causing frostbite.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquid helium, colder than liquid nitrogen, has also been used for cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Liquid helium boils at −269 °C (−452.20 °F), and temperatures ranging from −230 to −240 °C (−382.0 to −400.0 °F) have been measured from the heatsink.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] However, liquid helium is more expensive and more difficult to store and use than liquid nitrogen.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Also, extremely low temperatures can cause integrated circuits to stop functioning.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Silicon-based semiconductors, for example, will freeze out at around −233 °C (−387.4 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Commonly known as bong or boiler cooling, due to the outward appearance.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Water is atomized and blown through a heatsink with a fan.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The mist increases the surface area of water, which cools the water itself.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Ice can be added for lower temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Peltier junctions are generally only around 10–15% as efficient as the ideal refrigerator (Carnot cycle), compared with 40–60% achieved by conventional compression cycle systems (reverse Rankine systems using compression/expansion).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Due to this lower efficiency, thermoelectric cooling is generally only used in environments where the solid state nature (no moving parts, low maintenance, compact size, and orientation insensitivity) outweighs pure efficiency.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Modern TECs use several stacked units each composed of dozens or hundreds of thermocouples laid out next to each other, which allows for a substantial amount of heat transfer.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A combination of bismuth and tellurium is most commonly used for the thermocouples.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] As active heat pumps which consume power, TECs can produce temperatures below ambient, impossible with passive heatsinks, radiator-cooled liquid cooling, and heatpipe HSFs.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] However, while pumping heat, a Peltier module will typically consume more electric power than the heat amount being pumped.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] It is also possible to use a Peltier element together with a high pressure refrigerant (two phase cooling) to cool the CPU.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Phase-change cooling is an extremely effective way to cool the processor.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A vapor compression phase-change cooler is a unit that usually sits underneath the PC, with a tube leading to the processor.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Inside the unit is a compressor of the same type as in an air conditioner.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The compressor compresses a gas (or mixture of gases) which comes from the evaporator (CPU cooler discussed below).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The liquid evaporates (changing phase), absorbing the heat from the processor as it draws extra energy from its environment to accommodate this change (see latent heat).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The evaporation can produce temperatures reaching around −15 to −150 °C (5 to −238 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The liquid flows into the evaporator cooling the CPU, turning into a vapor at low pressure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] At the end of the evaporator this gas flows down to the compressor and the cycle begins over again.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This way, the processor can be cooled to temperatures ranging from −15 to −150 °C (5 to −238 °F), depending on the load, wattage of the processor, the refrigeration system (see refrigeration) and the gas mixture used.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This type of cooling is seen as a more extreme way to cool components since the units are relatively expensive compared to the average desktop.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] They also generate a significant amount of noise, since they are essentially refrigerators; however, the compressor choice and air cooling system is the main determinant of this, allowing for flexibility for noise reduction based on the parts chosen.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Another growing trend due to the increasing heat density of computers, GPUs, FPGAs, and ASICs is to immerse the entire computer or select components in a thermally, but not electrically, conductive liquid.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Although rarely used for the cooling of personal computers, liquid immersion is a routine method of cooling large power distribution components such as transformers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] It is also becoming popular with data centers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Personal computers cooled in this manner may not require either fans or pumps, and may be cooled exclusively by passive heat exchange between the computer hardware and the enclosure it is placed in.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A heat exchanger (i.e. heater core or radiator) might still be needed though, and the piping also needs to be placed correctly.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The coolant used must have sufficiently low electrical conductivity not to interfere with the normal operation of the computer.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] If the liquid is somewhat electrically conductive, it may cause electrical shorts between components or traces and permanently damage them.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] For these reasons, it is preferred that the liquid be an insulator (dielectric) and not conduct electricity.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] A wide variety of liquids exist for this purpose, including transformer oils, synthetic single-phase and dual phase dielectric coolants such as 3M Fluorinert or 3M Novec.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Non-purpose oils, including cooking, motor and silicone oils, have been successfully used for cooling personal computers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Some fluids used in immersion cooling, especially hydrocarbon-based materials such as mineral oils, cooking oils, and organic esters, may degrade some common materials used in computers such as rubbers, polyvinyl chloride (PVC), and thermal greases.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Therefore, it is critical to review the material compatibility of such fluids prior to use.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Mineral oil in particular has been found to have negative effects on PVC and rubber-based wire insulation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Thermal pastes used to transfer heat to heatsinks from processors and graphic cards has been reported to dissolve in some liquids, however with negligible impact to cooling, unless the components were removed and operated in air.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Evaporation, especially for 2-phase coolants, can pose a problem, and the liquid may require either to be regularly refilled or sealed inside the computer's enclosure.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Immersion cooling can allow for extremely low PUE values of 1.05, vs air cooling's 1.35, and allow for up to 100 KW of computing power (heat dissipation, TDP) per 19-inch rack, as opposed to air cooling, which usually handles up to 23 KW.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Where powerful computers with many features are not required, less powerful computers or ones with fewer features can be used.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] As of 2011 a VIA EPIA motherboard with CPU typically dissipates approximately 25 watts of heat, whereas a more capable Pentium 4 motherboard and CPU typically dissipates around 140 watts.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Computers can be powered with direct current from an external power supply unit which does not generate heat inside the computer case.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The replacement of cathode-ray-tube (CRT) displays by more efficient thin-screen liquid crystal display (LCD) ones in the early twenty-first century has reduced power consumption significantly.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Soft cooling is the practice of utilizing software to take advantage of CPU power saving technologies to minimize energy use.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This is done using halt instructions to turn off or put in standby state CPU subparts that aren't being used or by underclocking the CPU.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] While resulting in lower total speeds, this can be very useful if overclocking a CPU to improve user experience rather than increase raw processing power, since it can prevent the need for noisier cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Contrary to what the term suggests, it is not a form of cooling but of reducing heat creation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Undervolting is a practice of running the CPU or any other component with voltages below the device specifications.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] An undervolted component draws less power and thus produces less heat.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] The ability to do this varies by manufacturer, product line, and even different production runs of the same product (as well as that of other components in the system), but processors are often specified to use voltages higher than strictly necessary.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] This tolerance ensures that the processor will have a higher chance of performing correctly under sub-optimal conditions, such as a lower-quality motherboard or low power supply voltages.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Below a certain limit, the processor will not function correctly, although undervolting too far does not typically lead to permanent hardware damage (unlike overvolting).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] Undervolting is used for quiet systems, as less cooling is needed because of the reduction of heat production, allowing noisy fans to be omitted.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p01] It is also used when battery charge life must be maximized.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Cooling can be improved by several techniques, which may involve additional expense or effort.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] These techniques are often used, in particular, by those who run parts of their computer (such as the CPU and GPU) at higher voltages and frequencies than specified by the manufacturer (overclocking), which increases heat generation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] The installation of higher-performance, non-stock cooling may also be considered modding.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Many overclockers simply buy more efficient, and often, more expensive fan and heatsink combinations, while others resort to more exotic ways of computer cooling, such as liquid cooling, Peltier effect heatpumps, heat pipe or phase change cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Often called Thermal Interface Material (TIM).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Perfectly flat surfaces in contact give optimal cooling, but perfect flatness and absence of microscopic air gaps is not practically possible, particularly in mass-produced equipment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] A very thin skim of thermal compound, which is much more thermally conductive than air, though much less so than metal, can improve thermal contact and cooling by filling in the air gaps.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] If only a small amount of compound just sufficient to fill the gaps is used, the best temperature reduction will be obtained.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] There is much debate about the merits of compounds, and overclockers often consider some compounds to be superior to others.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] The main consideration is to use the minimal amount of thermal compound required to even out surfaces, as the thermal conductivity of compound is typically 1/3 to 1/400 that of metal, though much better than air.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] The conductivity of the heatsink compound ranges from about 0.5 to 80W/mK (see articles); that of aluminium is about 200, that of air about 0.02.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Heat-conductive pads are also used, often fitted by manufacturers to heatsinks.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] They are less effective than properly applied thermal compound, but simpler to apply and, if fixed to the heatsink, cannot be omitted by users unaware of the importance of good thermal contact, or replaced by a thick and ineffective layer of compound.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Unlike some techniques discussed here, the use of thermal compound or padding is almost universal when dissipating significant amounts of heat.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Mass-produced CPU heat spreaders and heatsink bases are never perfectly flat or smooth; if these surfaces are placed in the best contact possible, there will be air gaps that reduce heat conduction.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] This can easily be mitigated by the use of thermal compound, but for the best possible results surfaces must be as flat as possible.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] This can be achieved by a laborious process known as lapping, which can reduce CPU temperature by typically 2 °C (4 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Most older PCs use flat ribbon cables to connect storage drives (IDE or SCSI).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] These large flat cables greatly impede airflow by causing drag and turbulence.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Overclockers and modders often replace these with rounded cables, with the conductive wires bunched together tightly to reduce surface area.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Theoretically, the parallel strands of conductors in a ribbon cable serve to reduce crosstalk (signal-carrying conductors inducing signals in nearby conductors), but there is no empirical evidence of rounding cables reducing performance.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] This may be because the length of the cable is short enough so that the effect of crosstalk is negligible.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Problems usually arise when the cable is not electromagnetically protected and the length is considerable, a more frequent occurrence with older network cables.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] These computer cables can then be cable tied to the chassis or other cables to further increase airflow.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] This is less of a problem with computers that use serial ATA, which has a much narrower cable.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Newer computers improve this further by the common use of modular power supplies with removable cables, and cases with cable management areas behind the motherboard, leaving the front of the case free flowing.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] The colder the cooling medium (the air), the more effective the cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Fewer fans strategically placed will improve the airflow internally within the PC and thus lower the overall internal case temperature in relation to ambient conditions.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] The use of larger fans also improves efficiency and lowers the amount of waste heat along with the amount of noise generated by the fans while in operation.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] There is little agreement on the effectiveness of different fan placement configurations, and little in the way of systematic testing has been done.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] For a rectangular PC (ATX) case, a fan in the front with a fan in the rear and one in the top has been found to be a suitable configuration.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] However, AMD's (somewhat outdated) system cooling guidelines notes that "A front cooling fan does not seem to be essential.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] In fact, in some extreme situations, testing showed these fans to be recirculating hot air rather than introducing cool air." It may be that fans in the side panels could have a similar detrimental effect – possibly through disrupting the normal air flow through the case.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] However, this is unconfirmed and probably varies with the configuration.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Loosely speaking, positive pressure means intake into the case is stronger than exhaust from the case.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] This configuration results in pressure inside of the case being higher than in its environment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Negative pressure means exhaust is stronger than intake.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] This results in internal air pressure being lower than in the environment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Both configurations have benefits and drawbacks, with positive pressure being the more popular of the two configurations.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Negative pressure results in the case pulling air through holes and vents separate from the fans, as the internal gases will attempt to reach an equilibrium pressure with the environment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Consequently, this results in dust entering the computer in all locations.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Positive pressure in combination with filtered intake solves this issue, as air will only incline to be exhausted through these holes and vents in order to reach an equilibrium with its environment.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Dust is then unable to enter the case except through the intake fans, which need to possess dust filters.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Desktop computers typically use one or more fans for cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] For this reason, all modern ATX cases (with some exceptions found in ultra-low-budget cases) feature a power supply mount in the bottom, with a dedicated PSU air intake (often with its own filter) beneath the mounting location, allowing the PSU to draw cool air from beneath the case.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Most manufacturers recommend bringing cool, fresh air in at the bottom front of the case, and exhausting warm air from the top rear.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] If fans are fitted to force air into the case more effectively than it is removed, the pressure inside becomes higher than outside, referred to as a "positive" airflow (the opposite case is called "negative" airflow).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Worth noting is that positive internal pressure only prevents dust accumulating in the case if the air intakes are equipped with dust filters.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] The air flow inside the typical desktop case is usually not strong enough for a passive CPU heatsink.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Most desktop heatsinks are active, including one or even multiple directly attached fans or blowers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Each server can have an independent internal cooler system; Server cooling fans in (1 U) enclosures are usually located in the middle of the enclosure, between the hard drives at the front and passive CPU heatsinks at the rear.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Larger (higher) enclosures also have exhaust fans, and from approximately 4U they may have active heatsinks.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Power supplies generally have their own rear-facing exhaust fans.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Rack cabinet is a typical enclosure for horizontally mounted servers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Air typically drawn in at the front of the rack and exhausted at the rear.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Each cabinet can have additional cooling options; for example, they can have a Close Coupled Cooling attachable module or integrated with cabinet elements (like cooling doors in iDataPlex server rack).
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Another way of accommodating large numbers of systems in a small space is to use blade chassis, oriented vertically rather than horizontally, to facilitate convection.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Air heated by the hot components tends to rise, creating a natural air flow along the boards (stack effect), cooling them.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Some manufacturers take advantage of this effect.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Because data centers typically contain large numbers of computers and other power-dissipating devices, they risk equipment overheating; extensive HVAC systems are used to prevent this.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Often a raised floor is used so the area under the floor may be used as a large plenum for cooled air from a CRAC (Computer Room Air Conditioner) or a CRAH (Computer Room Air Handler) and power cabling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] A plenum made with a false ceiling can also be present.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Hot Aisle containment or cold aisle containment are also used in datacenters to improve cooling efficiency.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Alternatively slab floors can be used which are similar to conventional floors, and overhead ducts can be used for cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Direct Contact Liquid Cooling has emerged more efficient than air cooling options, resulting in smaller footprint, lower capital requirements and lower operational costs than air cooling.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] It uses warm liquid instead of air to move heat away from the hottest components.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Energy efficiency gains from liquid cooling is also driving its adoption.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Single and dual/two phase immersion/open tub cooling and single and dual phase direct-to-chip cooling as well as immersion cooling confined to individual server blades have also been proposed for use in data centers.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] In-row cooling, rack cooling, rear door heat exchangers, racktop cooling which places heat exchangers above the rack, overhead cooling above aisles or fan walls/thermal walls in a data center can also be used.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Direct Liquid Cooling (DLC) with cold plates for cooling chips in servers can be used due to the higher heat removal capacities of these systems.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] These systems can either cool some or all components on a server, using rubber or copper tubing respectively.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Rear door heat exchangers were traditionally used for cooling high heat densities in data centers, but these did not see widespread adoption.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] They can be cooled with refrigerant or chilled water.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Those cooled with chilled water can either be active, which have fans, or passive, which have no fans.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Liquid-to-air heat exchangers (radiators) can be used to cool servers cooled with direct-to-chip liquid cooling, in order to avoid installation of facility water piping.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] These heat exchangers can be installed separately from racks, or as a rear door on a rack.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Laptops present a difficult mechanical airflow design, power dissipation, and cooling challenge.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Constraints specific to laptops include: the device as a whole has to be as light as possible; the form factor has to be built around the standard keyboard layout; users are very close, so noise must be kept to a minimum, and the case exterior temperature must be kept low enough to be used on a lap.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Cooling generally uses forced air cooling but heat pipes and the use of the metal chassis or case as a passive heatsink are also common.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Solutions to reduce heat include using lower power consumption ARM or Intel Atom processors.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Mobile devices such as phones and tablets usually use passive cooling as mobile CPU and GPU chips are designed for maximum power efficiency due to the constraints of the device's battery.
[src:operating-temperature/computer-cooling-p02] Some higher-performance devices may include a heat spreader that aids in transferring heat to the external case of a phone or tablet.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In materials science, **creep** (sometimes called **cold flow**) is the tendency of a solid material to undergo slow deformation while subject to persistent mechanical stresses.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] It can occur as a result of long-term exposure to high levels of stress that are still below the yield strength of the material.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep is more severe in materials that are subjected to heat for long periods and generally increases as they near their melting point.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The rate of deformation is a function of the material's properties, exposure time, exposure temperature and the applied structural load.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Depending on the magnitude of the applied stress and its duration, the deformation may become so large that a component can no longer perform its function – for example creep of a turbine blade could cause the blade to contact the casing, resulting in the failure of the blade.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep is usually of concern to engineers and metallurgists when evaluating components that operate under high stresses or high temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep is a deformation mechanism that may or may not constitute a failure mode.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For example, moderate creep in concrete is sometimes welcomed because it relieves tensile stresses that might otherwise lead to cracking.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Unlike brittle fracture, creep deformation does not occur suddenly upon the application of stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Instead, strain accumulates as a result of long-term stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Therefore, creep is a "time-dependent" deformation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep or cold flow is of great concern in plastics.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Blocking agents are chemicals used to prevent or inhibit cold flow.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Otherwise rolled or stacked sheets stick together.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The temperature range in which creep deformation occurs depends on the material.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep deformation generally occurs when a material is stressed at a temperature near its melting point.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] While tungsten requires a temperature in the thousands of degrees before the onset of creep deformation, lead may creep at room temperature, and ice will creep at temperatures below 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Plastics and low-melting-temperature metals, including many solders, can begin to creep at room temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Glacier flow is an example of creep processes in ice.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The effects of creep deformation generally become noticeable at approximately 35% of the melting point (in Kelvin) for metals and at 45% of melting point for ceramics.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep behavior can be split into three main stages.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In primary or transient creep, the strain rate is a function of time.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In Class M materials, which include most pure materials, primary strain rate decreases over time.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This can be due to increasing dislocation density, or it can be due to evolving grain size.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In class A materials, which have large amounts of solid solution hardening, strain rate increases over time due to a thinning of solute drag atoms as dislocations move.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In the secondary, or steady-state, creep, dislocation structure and grain size have reached equilibrium, and therefore strain rate is constant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Equations that yield a strain rate refer to the steady-state strain rate.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Stress dependence of this rate depends on the creep mechanism.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In tertiary creep, the strain rate exponentially increases with stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This can be due to necking phenomena, internal cracks, or voids, which all decrease the cross-sectional area and increase the true stress on the region, further accelerating deformation and leading to fracture.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Depending on the temperature and stress, different deformation mechanisms are activated.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Though there are generally many deformation mechanisms active at all times, usually one mechanism is dominant, accounting for almost all deformation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At low temperatures and low stress, creep is essentially nonexistent and all strain is elastic.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At low temperatures and high stress, materials experience plastic deformation rather than creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At high temperatures and low stress, diffusional creep tends to be dominant, while at high temperatures and high stress, dislocation creep tends to be dominant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Deformation mechanism maps provide a visual tool categorizing the dominant deformation mechanism as a function of homologous temperature, shear modulus-normalized stress, and strain rate.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Generally, two of these three properties (most commonly temperature and stress) are the axes of the map, while the third is drawn as contours on the map.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] To populate the map, constitutive equations are found for each deformation mechanism.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] These are used to solve for the boundaries between each deformation mechanism, as well as the strain rate contours.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At high stresses (relative to the shear modulus), creep is controlled by the movement of dislocations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For dislocation creep, *Q* = *Q*(self diffusion), 4 ≤ *m* ≤ 6, and *b* < 1.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Therefore, dislocation creep has a strong dependence on the applied stress and the intrinsic activation energy and a weaker dependence on grain size.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] As grain size gets smaller, grain boundary area gets larger, so dislocation motion is impeded.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Some alloys exhibit a very large stress exponent (*m* > 10), and this has typically been explained by introducing a "threshold stress," *σ*th, below which creep can't be measured.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The modified power law equation then becomes: ${\frac {\mathrm {d} \varepsilon }{\mathrm {d} t}}=A\left(\sigma -\sigma _{\rm {th}}\right)^{m}e^{\frac {-Q}{{\bar {R}}T}}$ where *A*, *Q* and *m* can all be explained by conventional mechanisms (so 3 ≤ *m* ≤ 10), and *R* is the gas constant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The creep increases with increasing applied stress, since the applied stress tends to drive the dislocation past the barrier, and make the dislocation get into a lower energy state after bypassing the obstacle, which means that the dislocation is inclined to pass the obstacle.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In other words, part of the work required to overcome the energy barrier of passing an obstacle is provided by the applied stress and the remainder by thermal energy.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Nabarro–Herring (NH) creep is a form of diffusion creep, while dislocation glide creep does not involve atomic diffusion.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Nabarro–Herring creep dominates at high temperatures and low stresses.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] As shown in the figure on the right, the lateral sides of the crystal are subjected to tensile stress and the horizontal sides to compressive stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The atomic volume is altered by applied stress: it increases in regions under tension and decreases in regions under compression.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] So the activation energy for vacancy formation is changed by ±*σΩ*, where *Ω* is the atomic volume, the positive value is for compressive regions and negative value is for tensile regions.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In Nabarro–Herring creep, *k* is related to the diffusion coefficient of atoms through the lattice, *Q* = *Q*(self diffusion), *m* = 1, and *b* = 2.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Therefore, Nabarro–Herring creep has a weak stress dependence and a moderate grain size dependence, with the creep rate decreasing as the grain size is increased.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Nabarro–Herring creep is strongly temperature dependent.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For lattice diffusion of atoms to occur in a material, neighboring lattice sites or interstitial sites in the crystal structure must be free.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] A given atom must also overcome the energy barrier to move from its current site (it lies in an energetically favorable potential well) to the nearby vacant site (another potential well).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The general form of the diffusion equation is $D=D_{0}e^{\frac {E}{KT}}$ where *D*0 has a dependence on both the attempted jump frequency and the number of nearest neighbor sites and the probability of the sites being vacant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Thus there is a double dependence upon temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At higher temperatures the diffusivity increases due to the direct temperature dependence of the equation, the increase in vacancies through Schottky defect formation, and an increase in the average energy of atoms in the material.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Nabarro–Herring creep dominates at very high temperatures relative to a material's melting temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Coble creep is the second form of diffusion-controlled creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In Coble creep the atoms diffuse along grain boundaries to elongate the grains along the stress axis.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This causes Coble creep to have a stronger grain size dependence than Nabarro–Herring creep, thus, Coble creep will be more important in materials composed of very fine grains.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For Coble creep *k* is related to the diffusion coefficient of atoms along the grain boundary, *Q* = *Q*(grain boundary diffusion), *m* = 1, and *b* = 3.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Because *Q*(grain boundary diffusion) is less than *Q*(self diffusion), Coble creep occurs at lower temperatures than Nabarro–Herring creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Coble creep is still temperature dependent, as the temperature increases so does the grain boundary diffusion.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] However, since the number of nearest neighbors is effectively limited along the interface of the grains, and thermal generation of vacancies along the boundaries is less prevalent, the temperature dependence is not as strong as in Nabarro–Herring creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] It also exhibits the same linear dependence on stress as Nabarro–Herring creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Generally, the diffusional creep rate should be the sum of Nabarro–Herring creep rate and Coble creep rate.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Diffusional creep leads to grain-boundary separation, that is, voids or cracks form between the grains.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] To heal this, grain-boundary sliding occurs.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The diffusional creep rate and the grain boundary sliding rate must be balanced if there are no voids or cracks remaining.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] When grain-boundary sliding can not accommodate the incompatibility, grain-boundary voids are generated, which is related to the initiation of creep fracture.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Solute drag creep is one of the mechanisms for power-law creep (PLC), involving both dislocation and diffusional flow.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Solute drag creep is observed in certain metallic alloys.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In these alloys, the creep rate increases during the first stage of creep (Transient creep) before reaching a steady-state value.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This phenomenon can be explained by a model associated with solid–solution strengthening.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At low temperatures, the solute atoms are immobile and increase the flow stress required to move dislocations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] However, at higher temperatures, the solute atoms are more mobile and may form atmospheres and clouds surrounding the dislocations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This is especially likely if the solute atom has a large misfit in the matrix.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The solutes are attracted by the dislocation stress fields and are able to relieve the elastic stress fields of existing dislocations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Thus the solutes become bound to the dislocations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] When surrounded by a solute atmosphere, dislocations that attempt to glide under an applied stress are subjected to a back stress exerted on them by the cloud of solute atoms.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] If the applied stress is sufficiently high, the dislocation may eventually break away from the atmosphere, allowing the dislocation to continue gliding under the action of the applied stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The amount of "drag" exerted by the solute atoms on the dislocation is related to the diffusivity of the solute atoms in the metal at that temperature, with a higher diffusivity leading to lower drag and vice versa.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The velocity at which the dislocations glide can be approximated by a power law of the form $v=B{\sigma ^{*}}^{m}B=B_{0}\exp \left({\frac {-Q_{\rm {g}}}{RT}}\right)$ where *m* is the effective stress exponent, *Q* is the apparent activation energy for glide and *B*0 is a constant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] *c*0 and *D*sol are the atomic concentration of the solute and solute diffusivity respectively.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] *D*sol also has a temperature dependence that makes a determining contribution to *Q*g.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] If the cloud of solutes does not form or the dislocations are able to break away from their clouds, glide occurs in a jerky manner where fixed obstacles, formed by dislocations in combination with solutes, are overcome after a certain waiting time with support by thermal activation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The exponent *m* is greater than 1 in this case.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The equations show that the hardening effect of solutes is strong if the factor *B* in the power-law equation is low so that the dislocations move slowly and the diffusivity *D*sol is low.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Also, solute atoms with both high concentration in the matrix and strong interaction with dislocations are strong gardeners.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Since misfit strain of solute atoms is one of the ways they interact with dislocations, it follows that solute atoms with large atomic misfit are strong gardeners.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] A low diffusivity *D*sol is an additional condition for strong hardening.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Solute drag creep sometimes shows a special phenomenon, over a limited strain rate, which is called the Portevin–Le Chatelier effect.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] When the applied stress becomes sufficiently large, the dislocations will break away from the solute atoms since dislocation velocity increases with the stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] After breakaway, the stress decreases and the dislocation velocity also decreases, which allows the solute atoms to approach and reach the previously departed dislocations again, leading to a stress increase.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The process repeats itself when the next local stress maximum is obtained.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] So repetitive local stress maxima and minima could be detected during solute drag creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Dislocation climb-glide creep is observed in materials at high temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The initial creep rate is larger than the steady-state creep rate.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This process repeats itself each time when the dislocation encounters an obstacle.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The exponent *m* for dislocation climb-glide creep is 4.5 if *M* is independent of stress and this value of *m* is consistent with results from considerable experimental studies.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Harper–Dorn creep is a climb-controlled dislocation mechanism at low stresses that has been observed in aluminum, lead, and tin systems, in addition to nonmetal systems such as ceramics and ice.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] It was first observed by Harper and Dorn in 1957.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The same was also confirmed in 1972 by Barrett and co-workers where FeAl3 precipitates lowered the creep rates by 2 orders of magnitude compared to highly pure Al, thus, indicating Harper–Dorn creep to be a dislocation based mechanism.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Harper–Dorn creep is typically overwhelmed by other creep mechanisms in most situations, and is therefore not observed in most systems.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Twenty-five years after Harper and Dorn published their work, Mohamed and Ginter made an important contribution in 1982 by evaluating the potential for achieving Harper–Dorn creep in samples of Al using different processing procedures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The experiments showed that Harper–Dorn creep is achieved with stress exponent *n* = 1, and only when the internal dislocation density prior to testing is exceptionally low.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] By contrast, Harper–Dorn creep was not observed in polycrystalline Al and single crystal Al when the initial dislocation density was high.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] However, various conflicting reports demonstrate the uncertainties at very low stress levels.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] One report by Blum and Maier, claimed that the experimental evidence for Harper–Dorn creep is not fully convincing.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] They argued that the necessary condition for Harper–Dorn creep is not fulfilled in Al with 99.99% purity and the steady-state stress exponent *n* of the creep rate is always much larger than 1.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The subsequent work conducted by Ginter et al. confirmed that Harper–Dorn creep was attained in Al with 99.9995% purity but not in Al with 99.99% purity and, in addition, the creep curves obtained in the very high purity material exhibited regular and periodic accelerations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] They also found that the creep behavior no longer follows a stress exponent of *n* = 1 when the tests are extended to very high strains of >0.1 but instead there is evidence for a stress exponent of *n* > 2.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At high temperatures, it is energetically favorable for voids to shrink in a material.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The application of tensile stress opposes the reduction in energy gained by void shrinkage.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Thus, a certain magnitude of applied tensile stress is required to offset these shrinkage effects and cause void growth and creep fracture in materials at high temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This stress occurs at the *sintering limit* of the system.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The stress tending to shrink voids that must be overcome is related to the surface energy and surface area-volume ratio of the voids.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Below this critical stress, voids will tend to shrink rather than grow.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Additional void shrinkage effects will also result from the application of a compressive stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For typical descriptions of creep, it is assumed that the applied tensile stress exceeds the sintering limit.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep also explains one of several contributions to densification during metal powder sintering by hot pressing.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] A main aspect of densification is the shape change of the powder particles.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Since this change involves permanent deformation of crystalline solids, it can be considered a plastic deformation process and thus sintering can be described as a high temperature creep process.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The applied compressive stress during pressing accelerates void shrinkage rates and allows a relation between the steady-state creep power law and densification rate of the material.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] *A* and *n* are from the following form of the general steady-state creep equation, ${\dot {\varepsilon }}=A\sigma ^{n}$ where *ε̇* is the strain rate, and *σ* is the tensile stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep can occur in polymers and metals which are considered viscoelastic materials.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] When a polymeric material is subjected to an abrupt force, the response can be modeled using the Kelvin–Voigt model.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In this model, the material is represented by a Hookean spring and a Newtonian dashpot in parallel.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] When subjected to a step constant stress, viscoelastic materials experience a time-dependent increase in strain.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] This phenomenon is known as viscoelastic creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At a time *t*0, a viscoelastic material is loaded with a constant stress that is maintained for a sufficiently long time period.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The material responds to the stress with a strain that increases until the material ultimately fails.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] When the stress is maintained for a shorter time period, the material undergoes an initial strain until a time *t*1 at which the stress is relieved, at which time the strain immediately decreases (discontinuity) then continues decreasing gradually to a residual strain.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Viscoelastic creep data can be presented in one of two ways.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Total strain can be plotted as a function of time for a given temperature or temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Below a critical value of applied stress, a material may exhibit linear viscoelasticity.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Above this critical stress, the creep rate grows disproportionately faster.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The second way of graphically presenting viscoelastic creep in a material is by plotting the creep modulus (constant applied stress divided by total strain at a particular time) as a function of time.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Below its critical stress, the viscoelastic creep modulus is independent of the stress applied.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] A family of curves describing strain versus time response to various applied stress may be represented by a single viscoelastic creep modulus versus time curve if the applied stresses are below the material's critical stress value.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Additionally, the molecular weight of the polymer of interest is known to affect its creep behavior.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The effect of increasing molecular weight tends to promote secondary bonding between polymer chains and thus make the polymer more creep resistant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Similarly, aromatic polymers are even more creep resistant due to the added stiffness from the rings.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Both molecular weight and aromatic rings add to polymers' thermal stability, increasing the creep resistance of a polymer.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Polymers experience significant creep at temperatures above around −200 °C (−330 °F); however, there are three main differences between polymeric and metallic creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In metals, creep is not linearly viscoelastic, it is not recoverable, and it is only present at high temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Polymers show creep basically in two different ways.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] At typical work loads (5% up to 50%) ultra-high-molecular-weight polyethylene (Spectra, Dyneema) will show time-linear creep, whereas polyester or aramids (Twaron, Kevlar) will show a time-logarithmic creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Wood is considered as an orthotropic material, exhibiting different mechanical properties in three mutually perpendicular directions.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Experiments show that the tangential direction in solid wood tend display a slightly higher creep compliance than in the radial direction.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In the longitudinal direction, the creep compliance is relatively low and usually do not show any time-dependency in comparison to the other directions.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] It has also been shown that there is a substantial difference in viscoelastic properties of wood depending on loading modality (creep in compression or tension).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Studies have shown that certain Poisson's ratios gradually go from positive to negative values during the duration of the compression creep test, which does not occur in tension.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The creep of concrete, which originates from the calcium silicate hydrates (C-S-H) in the hardened Portland cement paste (which is the binder of mineral aggregates), is fundamentally different from the creep of metals as well as polymers.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Unlike the creep of metals, it occurs at all stress levels and, within the service stress range, is linearly dependent on the stress if the pore water content is constant.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Unlike the creep of polymers and metals, it exhibits multi-months aging, caused by chemical hardening due to hydration which stiffens the microstructure, and multi-year aging, caused by long-term relaxation of self-equilibrated microstresses in the nanoporous microstructure of the C-S-H.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] If concrete is fully cured, creep effectively ceases.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep in metals primarily manifests as movement in their microstructures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] While polymers and metals share some similarities in creep, the behavior of creep in metals displays a different mechanical response and must be modeled differently.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For example, with polymers, creep can be modeled using the Kelvin–Voigt model with a Hookean spring dashpot but with metals, the creep can be represented by plastic deformation mechanisms such as dislocation glide, climb and grain boundary sliding.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Understanding the mechanisms behind creep in metals is becoming increasingly more important for reliability and material lifetime as the operating temperatures for applications involving metals rise.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Unlike polymers, in which creep deformation can occur at very low temperatures, creep for metals typically occur at high temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Key examples would be scenarios in which these metal components like intermetallic or refractory metals are subject to high temperatures and mechanical loads like turbine blades, engine components and other structural elements.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Refractory metals, such as tungsten, molybdenum, and niobium, are known for their exceptional mechanical properties at high temperatures, proving to be useful materials in aerospace, defense and electronics industries.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Although mostly due to the reduced yield strength at higher temperatures, the collapse of the World Trade Center was thought to be due in part to creep from increased temperature, although this has since been disproven.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The creep rate of hot pressure-loaded components in a nuclear reactor at power can be a significant design constraint, since the creep rate is enhanced by the flux of energetic particles.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep in epoxy anchor adhesive was blamed for the Big Dig tunnel ceiling collapse in Boston, Massachusetts that occurred in July 2006.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The design of tungsten light bulb filaments attempts to reduce creep deformation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Sagging of the filament coil between its supports increases with time due to the weight of the filament itself.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] If too much deformation occurs, the adjacent turns of the coil touch one another, causing local overheating, which quickly leads to failure of the filament.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The coil geometry and supports are therefore designed to limit the stresses caused by the weight of the filament, and a special tungsten alloy with small amounts of oxygen trapped in the crystallite grain boundaries is used to slow the rate of Coble creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep can cause gradual cut-through of wire insulation, especially when stress is concentrated by pressing insulated wire against a sharp edge or corner.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Special creep-resistant insulations such as Kynar (polyvinylidene fluoride) are used in wire wrap applications to resist cut-through due to the sharp corners of wire wrap terminals.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Teflon insulation is resistant to elevated temperatures and has other desirable properties, but is notoriously vulnerable to cold-flow cut-through failures caused by creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In steam turbine power plants, pipes carry steam at high temperatures (566 °C, 1,051 °F) and pressures (above 24.1 MPa, 3,500 psi).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In jet engines, temperatures can reach up to 1,400 °C (2,550 °F) and initiate creep deformation in even advanced-design coated turbine blades.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Hence, it is crucial for correct functionality to understand the creep deformation behavior of materials.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep deformation is important not only in systems where high temperatures are endured such as nuclear power plants, jet engines and heat exchangers, but also in the design of many everyday objects.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For example, metal paper clips are stronger than plastic ones because plastics creep at room temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Aging glass windows are often erroneously used as an example of this phenomenon: measurable creep would only occur at temperatures above the glass transition temperature around 500 °C (932 °F).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] While glass does exhibit creep under the right conditions, apparent sagging in old windows may instead be a consequence of obsolete manufacturing processes, such as that used to create crown glass, which resulted in inconsistent thickness.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Fractal geometry, using a deterministic Cantor structure, is used to model the surface topography, where recent advancements in thermoviscoelastic creep contact of rough surfaces are introduced.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Various viscoelastic idealizations are used to model the surface materials, including the Maxwell, Kelvin–Voigt, standard linear solid and Jeffrey models.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Nimonic 75 has been certified by the European Union as a standard creep reference material.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The accepted practice when connecting stranded wire to a screw terminal is to use a wire ferrule on the end of the wire.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Generally, materials have better creep resistance if they have higher melting temperatures, lower diffusivity, and higher shear strength.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Close-packed structures are usually more creep resistant as they tend to have lower diffusivity than non-close-packed structures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Materials operating in high-performance systems, such as jet engines, often reach extreme temperatures surpassing 1,000 °C (1,830 °F), necessitating specialized material design.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Superalloys based on cobalt, nickel, and iron have been engineered to be highly resistant to creep.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The term 'superalloy' generally refers to austenitic nickel-, iron-, or cobalt-based alloys that use either γ′ or γ″ precipitation strengthening to maintain strength at high temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The γ′ phase is a cubic L12-structure Ni3(Al,Ti,Ta,Nb) phase that produces cuboidal precipitates.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Superalloys often have a high (60–75%) volume fraction of γ′ precipitates. γ′ precipitates are coherent with the parent γ phase, and are resistant to shearing due to the development of an anti-phase boundary when the precipitate is sheared.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The γ″ phase is a tetragonal Ni3Nb or Ni3V structure.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The γ″ phase, however, is unstable above 650 °C (1,202 °F), so γ″ is less commonly used as a strengthening phase in high temperature applications.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Carbides are also used in polycrystalline superalloys to inhibit grain boundary sliding.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Many other elements can be added to superalloys to tailor their properties.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] They can be used for solid solution strengthening, to reduce the formation of undesirable brittle precipitates, and to increase oxidation or corrosion resistance.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Nickel-based superalloys have found widespread use in high-temperature, low stress applications.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Iron-based superalloys are generally not used at high temperatures as the γ′ phase is not stable in the iron matrix, but are sometimes used at moderately high temperatures, as iron is significantly cheaper than nickel.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Cobalt-based γ′ structure was found in 2006, allowing the development of cobalt-based superalloys, which are superior to nickel-based superalloys in corrosion resistance.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] However, in the base (cobalt–tungsten–aluminum) system, γ′ is only stable below 900 °C (1,650 °F), and cobalt-based superalloys tend to be weaker than their Ni counterparts.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Based on the description of creep mechanisms and its three different stages mentioned earlier, creep resistance generally can be accomplished by using materials in which their tertiary stage is not active since, at this stage, the strain rate increases significantly by increasing stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The minimum value of creep rate is actually a constant creep rate, which plays a crucial role in designing a component, and its magnitude depends on temperature and stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The minimum value of creep rate that is commonly applied to alloys is based on two norms: (1) the stress required to produce a creep rate of 0.1%/h×10−3 and (2) the stress required to produce a creep rate of 0.1%/h×10−4, which takes roughly about 11.5 years.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The former standard has widely been used in the component design of turbine blades, while the latter is frequently used in designing steam turbines.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] One of the primary goals of creep tests is to determine the minimum value of the creep rate at the secondary stage and also to investigate the time required for an ultimate failure of a component.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] However, when it comes to ceramic applications, there are no such standards to determine their minimum creep rates, but ceramics are often chosen for high-temperature operations under load mainly because they possess a long lifetime.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] However, by acquiring information obtained from creep tests, proper ceramic material(s) can be selected for desired application to assure the safe service and evaluate the time period of secure service in high-temperature environments that the structural thermostability is essential.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Therefore, by making the proper choice, suitable ceramic components may be selected, capable of operating at various conditions of high temperature and creep deformation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Generally speaking, the structures of materials are different.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Metallic materials have different structures compared to polymer or ceramics, and even within the same class of materials, different structures might have existed at different temperatures.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The difference in the structure includes the difference in grains (for example, their sizes, shapes, and distributions), their crystalline or amorphous nature, and even dislocation and/or vacancy contents prone to change following a deformation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] So, since creep is a time-dependent process and differs from material to material, all these parameters must be considered in materials selection for a specific application.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For instance, materials with low-dislocation content are suitable for creep resistance.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In other words, the dislocation glide and climb can be reduced if the proper material is selected (for example, ceramic materials are very popular in this case).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] In terms of vacancies, the vacancy content not only depends on the chosen material but also on the component's service temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Vacancy-diffusion-controlled processes that promote creep can be categorized into grain boundary diffusion (Coble creep) and lattice diffusion (Nabarro–Herring creep).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Therefore, the properties of dislocations and vacancies, their distributions throughout the structure, and their potential change due to long-time exposure to stress and temperature must be considered seriously in materials selection for components design.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] For instance, different types of vacancies in ceramic materials have different charges stemming from their dominant chemical bonding.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] So, existing or newly-formed vacancies must be charge-balanced to maintain the overall neutrality of the final structure.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Besides paying attention to individual dislocation and vacancy contents, the correlation between them is also worth exploring since dislocation's ability to climb depends heavily on how many vacancies are available.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] To recap, materials must be selected and developed that possess low dislocation and vacancy contents to have a practical creep resistance component.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep is related to a material's melting point (*T*m).
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Generally, a high lifetime is expected when we have a higher melting point, and the reason behind selecting materials with high melting points originates from diffusion processes being related to temperature-dependent vacancy concentrations.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] The diffusion rate is slower in high-temperature materials.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Ceramic materials are well known for having high melting points, which is why ceramics attracted considerable attention to creep resistance applications.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Although it is widely known that creep starts at a temperature equal to 0.5‍*T*m, the safe temperature to avoid the initiation of creep is 0.3‍*T*m.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Creep that starts below or at 0.5‍*T*m is called "low temperature creep" because diffusion is not very progressive at such low temperatures, and the kind of creep that occurs is not diffusion-dominant and is related to other mechanisms.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] As mentioned previously, creep is a time-dependent deformation.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Fortunately, creep doesn't occur suddenly in brittle materials as it does under tension and other forms of deformation, and it is an advantage for designers.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Over time, creep strain develops in a material exposed to stress at the temperature of the application, and it depends on the duration of the exposure.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] Thus, the creep rate is also a function of time besides temperature and stress.
[src:operating-temperature/creep-deformation] It can be generalized as this function *ε* = *F*(*t*, *T*, *σ*) that tells the designer all the three parameters, including time, temperature, and stress acting in concert, and all of them must be considered if a successful creep-resistance component is to be attained.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] An **operating temperature** is the allowable temperature range of the local ambient environment at which an electrical or mechanical device operates.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] The device will operate effectively within a specified temperature range which varies on the basis of the device's function and application context, and ranges from the **minimum operating temperature** to the **maximum operating temperature** (or **peak operating temperature**).
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Outside this range of **safe operating temperatures** the device may fail.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] It is one component of reliability engineering.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Similarly, biological systems remain viable in a temperature range that equates to an operating temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Most semiconductor devices are manufactured in several temperature grades.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Nevertheless, each manufacturer defines its own temperature grades, so designers must pay attention to datasheet specifications.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] The use of such grades ensures that a device is suitable for its application and will withstand the environmental conditions in which it is used.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Normal operating temperature ranges are affected by several factors, such as the power dissipation of the device.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] These factors are used to define a "threshold temperature" of a device, i.e. its maximum normal operating temperature and a maximum operating temperature beyond which the device will no longer function.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Between these two temperatures, the device will operate at a non-peak level.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] For instance, a resistor may have a threshold temperature of 70 °C (158 °F) and a maximum temperature of 155 °C (311 °F), between which it exhibits a thermal derating.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Electrical and mechanical devices used in military and aerospace applications may need to endure greater environmental variability, including temperature range.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] In the United States Department of Defense has defined the United States Military Standard for all products used by the United States Armed Forces.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] A product's environmental design and test limits to the conditions that it will undergo throughout its service life are specified in MIL-STD-810, the *Department of Defense Test Method Standard for Environmental Engineering Considerations and Laboratory Tests*.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] The MIL-STD-810G standard specifies that the "operating temperature stabilization is attained when the temperature of the functioning part(s) of the test item considered to have the longest thermal lag is changing at a rate of no more than 2.0 °C (3.6 °F) per hour".
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] It also specifies procedures to assess the performance of materials to extreme temperature loads.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Military engine turbine blades experience two significant deformation stresses during normal service: creep and thermal fatigue.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Creep life of a material is "highly dependent on operating temperature", and creep analysis is thus an important part of design validation.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Some of the effects of creep and thermal fatigue may be mitigated by integrating cooling systems into the device's design, reducing the peak temperature experienced by the metal.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Commercial and retail products are manufactured to less stringent requirements than those for military and aerospace applications.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] For example, microprocessors produced by Intel Corporation are manufactured to three grades: commercial, industrial and extended.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Because some devices generate heat during operation, they may require thermal management to ensure they are within their specified operating temperature range; specifically, that they are operating at or below the maximum operating temperature of the device.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Cooling a microprocessor mounted in a typical commercial or retail configuration requires "a heatsink properly mounted to the processor, and effective airflow through the system chassis".
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Systems are designed to protect the processor from unusual operating conditions, such as "higher than normal ambient air temperatures or failure of a system thermal management component (such as a system fan)", though in "a properly designed system, this feature should never become active".
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Cooling and other thermal management techniques may affect performance and noise level.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Noise mitigation strategies may be required in residential applications to ensure that the noise level does not become uncomfortable.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Battery service life and efficacy is affected by operating temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Efficacy is determined by comparing the service life achieved by the battery as a percentage of its service life achieved at 20 °C (68 °F) versus temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Ohmic load and operating temperature often jointly determine a battery's discharge rate.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Moreover, if the expected operating temperature for a primary battery deviates from the typical 10 °C to 25 °C (50 to 77 °F) range, then operating temperature "will often have an influence on the type of battery selected for the application".
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Energy reclamation from partially depleted lithium sulfur dioxide battery has been shown to improve when "appropriately increasing the battery operating temperature".
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Mammals attempt to maintain a comfortable body temperature under various conditions by thermoregulation, part of mammalian homeostasis.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] The lowest normal temperature of a mammal, the basal body temperature, is achieved during sleep.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] In women, it is affected by ovulation, causing a biphasic pattern which may be used as a component of fertility awareness.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] In humans, the hypothalamus regulates metabolism, and hence the basal metabolic rate.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Amongst its functions is the regulation of body temperature.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] The core body temperature is also one of the classic phase markers for measuring the timing of an individual's circadian rhythm.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] Changes to the normal human body temperature may result in discomfort.
[src:operating-temperature/operating-temperature] The most common such change is a fever, a temporary elevation of the body's thermoregulatory set-point, typically by about 1–2 °C (1.8–3.6 °F).
